<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 94 / Overseas earnings by consultants fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The net overseas earnings of UK professional consultants fell slightly last
year, figures released by the Central Statistical Office yesterday show.
Consultants, defined as including professions such as engineers, architects
and accountants, earned a net Pounds 1.34bn last year, down from Pounds
1.41bn in 1992. The biggest contribution came from the legal profession,
which earned a net Pounds 500m, up from Pounds 473m in 1992.
Accountants and surveyors recorded the sharpest increases in net overseas
earnings over the two years, but there were steep declines in the earnings
recorded by architects and advertisers. Apart from lawyers, consulting
engineers made the biggest contribution, with net earnings of Pounds 240m.
The biggest market for UK consultants was the European Union, with 49 per
cent of the net total. Asia was second, with 24 per cent. The UK had only a
small surplus with the Americas, mainly because its imports from the region
were higher than from any other area.
The net overseas earnings of consultants have declined steadily in recent
years, after peaking at Pounds 1.61bn in 1990.
</TEXT>
