<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 94 / BBC secures lottery showtime
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Camelot, the National Lottery operator, has reached agreement with the BBC
on televising the draw that could create millionaires most weeks between
November 19 and September 2001.
An official announcement of the deal, the result of months of negotiations
between Camelot, the BBC and the Office of the National Lottery, is expected
early next month.
The hope is that the opening hour-long programme, to be hosted by Noel
Edmonds, might top the UK television ratings with a potential audience of
between 18m and 20m. The expectation is that the regular half-hour programme
will probably be scheduled at about 8pm on BBC 1 and could challenge
programmes such as Coronation Street and EastEnders for the top slot in the
ratings.
All around the world live television is a big part of generating publicity
and excitement for national lotteries. The Camelot-BBC approach is for a
relatively unusual programme by international standards - there are unlikely
to be magicians or dancing girls.
Choosing the six winning numbers out of 49, with a seventh ball to chose
intermediate Pounds 100,000 winners, is likely to take only a couple of
minutes. One of the formats under consideration would involve other games of
chance. Other elements could involve good news - human interest stories of
winners and how the prizes will affect their lives, although players will
have a right to privacy if they choose.
As money starts to flow to the five good causes which will benefit from the
National Lottery proceeds - the arts, charities, a millennium fund, the
national heritage and sports - there will also be stories about how the
money is being spent. The programme will be under the overall control of Mr
Michael Leggo, head of entertainment at BBC Television.
When Camelot launches its scratch-cards in addition to the main computerised
draw in the spring there will be a second mid-week programme.
The Camelot consortium, which brings together Cadbury Schweppes, Racal
Electronics, De La Rue, GTech and ICL, wanted to launch with the BBC from
the start.
Not only was the corporation seen as the right environment to launch what
Camelot hopes will become a national institution in its own right, but the
BBC could also offer national, regional and local radio coverage.
The Camelot approach has been to try to get the best of both worlds by
putting the draw live on BBC and advertising the lottery on ITV.
ITV, which ruled itself out of the competition to broadcast the draw and
scratch-card competitions - largely, it said, because of regulatory
difficulties, will almost certainly run the winning numbers within seconds
of the BBC draw.
Mr Nicholas Hinton, the chief executive of the Millennium Commission, was
last night dismissed just before formally taking office.
The issue that led to Mr Hinton's departure - his appointment was due to
become permanent on Monday morning - appears to have involved a definition
of his role. The commissioners may have been more 'hands-on' than Mr Hinton
expected.
Mr Michael Montague, one of the millennium commissioners, said last night:
'I felt either we accepted the way things were developing or we did
something about it and the right time was before Monday.'
</TEXT>
