<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 94 / Russian central bank chief offers to quit over rouble
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The chairman of Russia's central bank offered his resignation in a letter to
President Boris Yeltsin, at the end of a turbulent week in Russian currency
markets.
Mr Yeltsin signed a decree formally relieving Mr Boris Gerashchenko of his
post. The state Duma (lower house of parliament) had been due to vote on an
earlier presidential request to remove Mr Gerashchenko next Wednesday, and
there was confusion following Mr Yeltsin's decree on whether it would still
be debated.
The news was greeted by Mr Boris Fyodorov, the former reformist finance
minister, who wants Mr Gerashchenko's job, with the comment: 'There's
evidently still a God in heaven.'
The rouble, which fell heavily early in the week, strengthened further
yesterday after a recovery on Thursday, rising 6 points to end the day at
2,988 to the dollar. However, the market remained jumpy: Mr Igor Doronin,
the marketing adviser to the Moscow Interbank Currency Exchange, said the
central bank had deliberately run the currency down this week and warned
that a further crash could destroy the exchange.
Mr Fyodorov's delight at the offered resignation of his long-time opponent
contrasted with statements from Mr Yegor Gaidar, leader of the Russia's
Choice group, who said Mr Gerashchenko was 'right to take responsibility on
himself', and Mr Grigory Yavlinsky, leader of the Yabloko group, who said
that he had acted 'like a real man'.
The candidates for Mr Gerashchenko's chair would include Mr Fyodorov, Mr
Dmitri Tulin, a bank deputy chairman with a good reputation with western
banks, and Ms Tatyana Paramanova, also a deputy chairman, noted for refusing
credits.
The move comes as the government prepares for talks with the International
Monetary Fund, whose team arrives today. The talks centre on a Dollars 4bn
(Pounds 2.5bn) fund to stabilise the currency, and the IMF will press for
detailed and closely monitored monetary and fiscal dealings.
It does not intend to support a budget for 1995 unless the government's aims
include reducing inflation to about 3 per cent or lower a month, and
achieving a budget deficit of about 5 per cent of gross national product
next year - compared with a present level of about 11 per cent.
Mr Jeffrey Sachs, an economist and former Russian government adviser, said
yesterday that 'whatever happened this week, the basic reason is that the
government has not put in place clear rules of the game - and so the power
of a few insiders to stop reform is still too great'.
Rouble row, Page 2
Currencies, Page 13
From Russia with confidence, Weekend V
</TEXT>
