<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / London Stock Exchange: Cadbury weaken
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON, PETER JOHN, JOEL KIBAZO and JEFFREY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The prospect of stiffer competition in the cola market sent confectionery
and soft drinks group Cadbury-Schweppes tumbling 12 to 438p, as 9.3m shares
were traded, the highest daily total for four years.
Confirmation that Tesco is to have exclusive rights to sell Mr Richard
Branson's Virgin Cola for at least six months, appeared to be the trigger
for the latest slide in the stock. The shares fell on Wednesday after an
announcement that Virgin group is to launch its own brand cola.
Market watchers first thought the new product, whose syrup is to be made by
Cott Corporation of Canada, would be distributed largely through independent
retailers, thus posing less threat to Cadbury's soft drinks market share.
A joint venture between Cadbury and Coca-Cola bottles, cans and distributes
Coca-Cola and Cadbury beverages brands in the UK. Analysts said the deal
with Tesco was likely to give Virgin its target market share of around 7 per
cent of the UK retail market.
Miss Arabella Cecil, at Credit Lyonnais, said: 'If the Virgin cola meets Mr
Branson's volume targets, Cott Corporation's products will achieve a 20 per
cent market share in the UK.' Shares in Tesco hardened 2 1/2 to 239 1/2 p.
</TEXT>
