<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / London Stock Exchange: Telecoms attract buyers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON, PETER JOHN, JOEL KIBAZO and JEFFREY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The telecoms stocks, in the forefront of the market's upsurge of recent
days, continued to make good progress yesterday with Cable and Wireless
leading the pack higher again, and with buying stimulated by a 40-page buy
note published by Hoare Govett. C &amp; W rose 5 more to 426p on turnover of
10m.
Hoare described C &amp; W shares as having 'further to go' and highlighted its
500p price target for the shares.
The broker said C &amp; W's entire market capitalisation is now less than the
value of its holdings in HK Telecom and in 23 cellular groups around the
world, leaving Mercury and the rest in the price for free.
Hoare said that if floated independently these operations would be worth
Pounds 3.6bn, equivalent to the value of a middle-ranking FT-SE 100 company.
The prospects of a potential bid for the group was also mentioned by Hoare.
He said that eight of the world's top 10 telecoms companies are involved in
important deals.
The broker cited AT &amp; T, US West, Pacific Telses and Hutchison as potential
bidders/partners for C &amp; W: 'It is even conceivable that BT could buy C &amp; W
for its presence in the far east and then sell off Mercury.'
</TEXT>
