<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / London Stock Exchange: US price statistics drive share
prices higher - Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND, UK Stock Market Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A UK stock market trading cautiously in the first half of yesterday's
session exploded with confidence after an unexpected fall in US producer
price figures in September triggered a sharp rise on Wall Street and in
global bond markets.
After showing little change at mid-session, the FT-SE 100 share index jumped
by more than 50 points on the US data, before closing a net 41.4 points up
at 3,141.9. Trading volume jumped by nearly 12 per cent.
The market's optimistic mood was helped by a buoyant speech at the
Conservative Party Conference from Mr Kenneth Clarke, the UK chancellor of
the exchequer, in which he reiterated the government's firm stance against
inflation. The Bundesbank's decision to leave German rates unchanged was no
surprise but buttressed confidence that upward pressures on world rates are
slackening.
The fall of 0.5 per cent in US September producer prices, and a gain of 0.1
per cent in the core rate, reduced the threat of an early tightening in
Federal Reserve credit policy and lends support to confidence that the
recovery in the US economy can be achieved without increasing inflationary
pressures.
However, some analysts warned that today brings another round of important
statistics on the US economy, including the consumer price index, industrial
production and capacity utilisation numbers. These could still present a
challenge to optimistic views on US economic recovery and interest rate
prospects.
In the early part of the session, share prices were easier until stock index
futures opened firmly. Even then, however, share prices trod water, with
investors appearing unwilling to drive the recovery in the stock market any
further. Wednesday evening saw an apparent slackening in the pace of the
stock market upswing, although traders showed unwillingness to take profits.
Active features included the defence sector, where disclosure that GEC had
declared interest in the VSEL bid situation alerted investors. The market
appeared unsure whether GEC would bid - its shares advanced yesterday - and
VSEL, although still above the British Aerospace terms, made only a modest
response to the news.
But the gain on the FT-SE 100 Index jumped from 3 points to 23 points within
the hour which included announcement of the US price data. The chief impetus
came from bond markets but the December contract on the Footsie also led the
way ahead, moving above 3,178 at the day's peak and showing a good premium
against the underlying stock market.
The influence of the stock index future contract implied a focus on the
blue-chip Footsie 100 stocks. The FT-SE Mid 250 index, taking in a range of
second line issues, gained only 21.3 points for a close of 3,556.6. Trading
in non-Footsie stocks made up around 55 per cent of total business
yesterday.
Although gains were fairly evenly spread across the range of the market, it
was the US-influenced stocks which stood out at the close of trading in
London, when the Dow Industrial Average was ahead by 38 points in early
trading.
The FT-SE 100 share index has risen by just over 185 points since its return
to the bull tack a week ago. This is a heartening development for analysts
who had predicted that by the year-end, the Footsie would be in the 3,400
plus range.
Market traders now hope that subdued inflationary pressures will enable base
rates to remain at their present levels for the rest of the year, while
economic recovery shows through more clearly, bringing higher earnings and
dividend payouts from leading British companies.
</TEXT>
<XX>
