<PROFILE>_AN-EJND7AG4FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941014
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / World Stock Markets: Market activity declines
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Declines in activity in Europe's two biggest equity markets, Germany and the
UK, brought total turnover at the eight bourses measured by NatWest
Securities down by 3.5 per cent in September after the substantial, 10.7 per
cent rise in August.
However, says Mr James Cornish at NatWest, the fall was by no means uniform;
five of the eight saw turnover gains although share prices fell overall with
the FT-Acturaries Europe index down 6.4 per cent, after the July/August
summer rally which took them 7.8 per cent higher.
Mr Cornish adds that international investors returned after a summer lull,
with turnover in European stocks traded on Seaq International in London
rising to a 'normal' 16.2 per cent of that in continental domestic markets
from 15.2 per cent in the month before.
The star performers in volume terms last month were: France, where turnover
rose 15.8 per cent although the share price index dropped 8.6 per cent;
Italy, with a 12.5 per cent gain after a 15.9 per cent August drop -
reflecting hopes that Mr Silvio Berlusconi, the Italian prime minister, was
getting his political act together; Spain, where a rise of 11.9 per cent in
Madrid volumes contrasted with a drop of 16.4 per cent via the Spanish Seaq
International market in London; and Belgium, which saw business up 10.7 per
cent on top of a 29.4 per cent rise in August.
