<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: The 'grass roots' strategy for
holding back the deserts - Efforts to involve local people more in the
battle against land degradation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEOFF TANSEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
About 100 governments are expected to sign a new convention to combat
desertification at the Paris headquarters of the United Nations Educational,
Scientific and Cultural Organisation during a two-day conference starting
today.
Two fifths of the earth's land surface, with a fifth of the population, are
drylands susceptible to desertification. However, just how much land is
desertified and what desertification is - over 100 definitions have appeared
in the past 20 years - have been hotly debated.
Since the first desertification conference in 1977, the UN's own estimates
of the areas affected have fallen dramatically from about three-quarters of
drylands to less than a quarter, says Professor David Thomas, director of
the Sheffield Centre for International Drylands Research, Sheffield
University, in his recently published book Desertification: Exploding the
Myth.
In the convention, desertification is defined as 'land degradation in arid,
semi-arid and dry sub-humid tropics'. At the Rio Earth Summit in 1992, from
which the new convention emerged during follow-up negotiations, climatic
variation was added to human activities as a cause of desertification. This,
fears Prof Thomas, could be used as an excuse to avoid supporting the local
actions necessary to combat desertification caused by people.
Soil degradation is the key indicator of land degradation. Overall, about 20
per cent of the world's soils are degraded according to the latest global
survey. This was based on a computer database using local assessments of
degradation. If the light degradation category is omitted, as this covers
minor changes that can be easily reversed, the figure comes down to about 12
per cent.
Europe's relatively high figure applies mainly to the semi-arid lands around
the Mediterranean, while the low figure for Australia's dry land is because
most of the changes relate to vegetation in rangelands rather than the soil
itself, notes Prof Thomas.
Most degradation is caused by water and wind erosion, followed by chemical
degradation (salination, alkalination and nutrient loss) and physical
degradation (mainly compacting and crusting). About 6m hectares of land are
lost to desertification each year according to UN Environment Programme 1991
estimates.
Wherever it occurs the effects can be devastating for the people involved.
Many villagers near Hodeidha in Northern Tihama in Yemen, for example, have
lost their houses to encroaching sands. For 10,000 years, all but the farmed
areas of Yemen were covered by trees. Even the hot, dry coastal and inland
fringes of desert were thick with acacia until 30 years ago. But, for the
past few decades, traders have bought the trees for charcoal or building
materials. Over 1,000 sq km of desert have been created according to World
Bank reports, says Mr Tony Milroy of the Arid Lands Initiative, a small non
governmental organisation (NGO) working with local communities in rural
Yemen.
Elsewhere in Tihama, herders can still graze their goats on trees because
villagers have maintained the traditional practice of not cutting down live
trees. Other communities have organised their children to collect seeds and
local farmers are planting them into the denuded soil to re-establish cover,
using techniques from Australia, says Mr Milroy.
The common image of desertification is shifting sand dunes obliterating land
and housing. But this is true only in very specific and limited
circumstances, like those in Yemen, and not in much of the area fringing the
Sahara.
There has been a serious misunderstanding of how semi-arid areas adapt to
the large fluctuations in climatic conditions normal in those areas, says
Prof Thomas. Arid and semi-arid areas may have, for example, 15 to 20 years
with relative high rainfall then a similar period with little rain. The
vegetation dies off and the desert appears to advance but when rain returns,
so does the vegetation. People living in these semi-arid regions have also
adapted - moving their herds and varying their size, according to
conditions.
It is when other factors affect how the land is managed that desertification
arises - social and economic changes and population pressures may lead to
overcultivation, overgrazing, deforestation and poor irrigation practices,
any of which can trigger desertification. These vary in different regions,
making desertification not a single global problem with one solution but a
problem with global dimensions, many causes and many solutions. It needs not
grand global and national plans, but planning with and action by local
people, building on the systems used in many of these areas for centuries,
believes Prof Thomas.
Although the new convention's provisions are broad and often vague, unlike
earlier work it specifically stresses 'the importance of ensuring the full
participation of men and women at all levels in programmes to combat
desertification and mitigate the effects of drought'.
The problem, says Mr Milroy, is that neither the UN and national governments
lack structures suitable for working closely with local people. 'Our
research and documentation of practical success stories shows that
grass-roots initiatives that involve the real experts, local farmers,
livestock herders that have subsisted in low-rainfall areas for millenniums,
cannot only succeed but can be replicated at low cost without the
involvement of outside expertise.'
He and Prof Thomas are sceptical about the value of national plans and both
urge greater support and encouragement to NGOs able and willing to work with
local groups. Up to 50 NGOs from all over the globe will meet in Burkina
Faso in early November to ensure grass roots follow-up to the convention.
They will develop the networking abilities and pay particular attention to a
strategy for Africa.
Four videos, in Arabic, English and French, showing the ARI's experience
working with Yemen's farmers are available from ALI, Machpelah Works,
Burnley Road, Hebden Bridge, W. Yorks, HX7 8AU, UK. Tel: 44 1422 843807,
Fax: 44 1422 842241.
