<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: UK to present proposals for
opening Irish fishery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain presents its proposals to the European Commission today for opening
up European Union waters around Ireland to the Spanish and Portuguese
fishing fleets from 1996.
At the last fisheries council in September, a Commission proposal was
rejected as being too bureaucratic and unworkable. The Commission called for
member countries' own ideas on providing access to these sensitive waters
when Spain and Portugal become full members of the common fisheries policy
at the end of next year.
Mr Michael Jack, fisheries minister, said the British suggestions reflected
many of the views of fishermen after widespread consultation. 'Now, we need
to convince the council we have a workable alternative to the Commission's
proposal,' he said. He hoped the issue would be discussed at the next
fisheries council in November.
Spain had threatened to block the accession of Austria, Norway, Finland and
Sweden EU if rules for accommodating Spanish fishermen were not agreed by
the end of this year.
Mr Jack is calling for access to waters west of the UK, France and
north-west Spain to be restricted to vessels with established rights, with
special treatment for highly sensitive zones such as the Irish Box.
He wants the UK to be able to enforce access arrangements for all vessels in
its western waters. In addition, he wants larger vessels to be required to
report their entry into and exit from areas covered by the regulations and
to report catches. He is also proposing stronger technical conservation
measures.
The Commission had suggested allocation of standard vessel days to each
nation for fishing in these waters.
</TEXT>
