<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / Survey of International Standards (5): UK has 36 official
groups
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SHEILA JONES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Quality control in the UK is carried out by 36 accredited bodies, the
largest and best-known of which is the British Standards Institution, writes
Sheila Jones.
These bodies assess management and production systems as well as product
quality. Before operating, they are assessed by the National Accreditation
Council for Certification Bodies, the central organisation responsible for
ensuring that those seeking the right to give products their stamp of
approval have first won approval themselves. Once an approved body is up and
running, it is reviewed by the NACCB twice a year and reassessed every four
years.
In the global markets of the 1990s, manufacturers ignore quality systems and
standards 'at their peril,' according to Mr Paul Hewlett, who has just
retired as NACCB secretary.
His successor, Mr Robin Bullock-Webster, takes over at the NACCB at a
difficult time. The way in which quality control and certification is
carried out in the UK has been much criticised in recent years. The
criticism reached a crescendo earlier this year with the publication of a
report - UK Quality Management - by the Science and Engineering Policy
Studies Unit. The report asserted, among other things, that there was little
to inspire confidence in a system that attracted its 'share of cowboys'.
Mr Bullock-Webster concedes it is legal for anyone to set themselves up as a
quality control assessor without NACCB approval. In addition to the 36
approved bodies, there are many organisations and consultancies selling
advice on the implementation of standards and quality control.
'In this country there are many hundreds of consultants making a living out
of 5750 (the BSI's production systems standard). I'm sure that the vast
majority of those are fair, reasonable level-headed and well-meaning. There
are inevitably some that are not.'
Certification that is 'meaningful', says Mr Bullock-Webster, is 'that which
has gone through the accredited process. There are possibly some 30,000
certificates which are now accredited on the market within the UK and I
think that that probably, to a degree, speaks for itself. I'm not saying
that we've got it all right, but we are trying to ensure that we do control
the situation.'
The NACCB has tightened up its surveillance of certification bodies and is
carrying out market research among UK businesses 'to establish exactly where
they think we're going right or where they think we're going wrong'. It is
also running workshops on quality control and the NACCB's role.
A further criticism, of the relationship between the NACCB and the BSI, has
prompted the two organisations to break a link that has existed since the
NACCB was set up. The BSI is itself split into two sections: BSI, which sets
British standards; and BSI-QA, the quality assurance arm. BSI-QA is just
another NACCB-approved certification body, perhaps best-known for its kite
mark stamp of approval on products. However, the BSI is also responsible for
NACCB funding. Mr Bullock-Webster points out that the while funding for pay
and administration is chanelled through the BSI, the organisation has no
involvement in policy, pay levels or recruitment. Nonetheless, the
'umbilical cord will be cut some time shortly.'
The decision to break the link follows assessment of the NACCB last year by
the European umbrella body for accreditation bodies, the EAC, as part of the
process of harmonisation. The EAC broadly approved of the NACCB's operations
but it felt that the BSI link 'could be construed as tying us rather too
closely to the BSI,' according to Mr Bullock-Webster.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
