<PROFILE>_AN-EJND7AGNFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941014
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / Survey of International Standards (2): Towards global
awareness - Environmental issues
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Black South African families in the Johannesburg township of Soweto are
buying their first electric fridges. As the Soweto electrification programme
proceeds, they are joining the consumer boom, and no-one is going to stop
them. Certainly not anyone who has experienced the consequences of having a
mesh-wire cupboard on legs as the sole aid to preserving perishable
foodstuffs in the heat of an African summer.
First-time consumers, along with many others across the world, probably do
not have environmental matters high on their shopping list. But that will
change, according to Mr John Kean, vice-president for technical management
for the International Organisation for Standardisation (Iso), who is also
chief executive of the Canadian Standards Association.
'There has to be education. The new consumer, just coming into
electrification for the first time, may not look for the same level of
standards that experienced users take for granted. But I think the global
communication we have today - such as instant television, and so on - is
ensuring a higher level of education about this issue.
'People want a say in things, and this is going to be just as much the case
in third world countries. I think it may be surprising how quickly awareness
spreads. People are on the global information highway: they really do have
instant access to information. A TV watcher in Soweto can see programmes on
a manufacturing problem in Birmingham, or anywhere else in the world.'
In the UK, the consumers of the future - the present generation of
schoolchildren - take a close interest in environmental issues. They nag
their parents as never before about using aerosols, recycling packaging, and
buying eco-friendly products. Consumer awareness of the environment and its
well-being has never been so high in developed countries, aided by the
publicity surrounding such events as the Earth Summit in Rio in June 1992.
Retailers and manufacturers are experiencing a pincer movement, from
consumers at one end, and regulators at the other. Yet the majority of
dangers do not come from the products visible on the supermarket shelf.
'Environmental issues are business issues,' declares Mr Lawrence Eicher,
secretary-general of Iso. 'The environmental standards that we develop
internationally will not only affect corporate profitability and world
trade, they will also affect the livelihood and health of millions of
people.'
Policing is not enough, argue those concerned in environmental matters.
Environmental concern has to be designed into the entire life cycle of
products and, just as important, services.
Nowhere is the rule of 'what can't be measured can't be delivered' more
difficult to apply. Replying to the sceptical, Mr Eicher points to Iso 9000
and its remarkable success as a quality measure in manufacturing, industry
and commerce in more than 50 countries.
Spreading the Iso 9000 principle to environmental issues is the aim of Iso
14000. The starting point is a set of rules for managing environmental
issues, which will create a worldwide yardstick.
Iso has been developing environmental standards since 1947, when one of its
first published standards dealt with acoustics. The issue of 'sustainable
development' has been on its agenda for more than 20 years.
'Environmental problems are by their nature international, and can only be
solved at international level,' reads an Iso bulletin from 1972. 'All laws,
regulations and standards concerning air and water should repose on the same
scientific and technological base. By developing the appropriate
international standards, Iso can provide that base.'
Already there are more than 350 international standards with environmental
relevance on the Iso's books. They include Iso/TC 22, Road Vehicles, which
has developed numerous standards related to exhaust emissions, and other
Iso/TC (Technical Committee) standards on nuclear energy, plastics
biodegradability, heating efficiency and emissions, and solid waste
management.
More recently it has risen to meet the challenges of setting environmental
standards with a number of initiatives. The committee Iso/TC 207, on
environmental management, was set up in January 1993 following two years of
work by Sage - the Strategic Advisory Group on Environment. Sage was the
result of co-operation between the Iso and the IEC, the authority
responsible for global standardisation in the electrical and electronics
fields.
Both organisations have spent years developing voluntary standards as
guidance for industry and regulatory authorities on environmental issues.
The IEC had its own Advisory Committee on Environmental Aspects to promote
and co-ordinate efforts.
Sage's job was to examine the problems and potential solutions afresh, and
come up with co-ordinated strategies. The result is TC 207, a committee
whose brief includes co-ordination and co-operation with international and
regional governmental bodies, including the European Union, General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, Organisation for Economic Co-operation and
Development, and many others.
The TC 207 sub-committees cover management systems, auditing, labelling,
performance evaluation and life cycle assessment. Early work includes a
guide for the inclusion of environmental aspects in product standards, and
standards for environmental management systems.
Mr Kean is an evangelist for Iso 14000. 'The environment is something we're
all part of, and we have to protect it for future generations. By focusing
on management, we're trying to get people to think ahead; address issues so
that they are thinking about the environment on a day-to-day basis. It has
to be pro-active rather than reactive.'
The standards should prompt designers to think about a product's impact on
the environment. The checklist of design requirements covers how an item
will be produced, used, and eventually disposed of, and what effects all
stages of the process will have on the environment.
'It has to be a systems approach, involving the whole process, from
conception to grave,' adds Mr Kean. 'We can never be 100 per cent sure of
effects, but we can be better equipped to ask the right questions.'
There are drawbacks. At last month's Iso conference on the environment, in
Nice - and entitled 'A challenge for international standardisation'  - the
president of the French movement Generation Ecologie, Mr Brice Lalonde,
pointed out that countries whose industries applied the standards could find
themselves disadvantaged if built-in environmental standards resulted in
higher costs than those of less careful competitors.
Having a measure might encourage participation by some of the companies who
have been watching the process nervously from the sidelines. So thinks Gib
Hedstrom, who, after 20 years in environmental auditing in the US recently
took up an appointment as vice-president of the the environmental health and
safety practice at Arthur D Little in Brussels.
'A standard takes some of the fear away,' he says. 'If we have a measure, we
can start to manage. Then we can move away from the litigious, defensive
position that what you can't measure, can't be used against you, to a caring
and sharing situation where former competitors and adversaries co-operate
and share data on emissions.'
Standards focus attention on the issues, and fuel investment in the
development of alternative technologies. Consumers react to environmental
issues, whether at the level of buying eco-friendly washing powder or
investing in ethical funds. But 'green' environmentalists argue that
standards are based on what is possible, rather than what is necessary.
Even so there is a catch: the long-term effects of our efforts can hold
unpleasant surprises. Clean, efficient nuclear power brought about the
Chernobyl disaster. Asbestos, once thought a boon for insulation, has proved
to be a killer in human lungs.
Many environmentally-aware people have in recent years espoused diesel
engines in their cars. But a recent report from the Ashden Trust indicated
that the rise in childhood asthma in the UK was directly attributable to
high levels of emissions from such car engines.
Many schoolchildren take for granted the car rides to and from school:
two-car families are on the increase.
It is a sad example of environmental irony if the youngsters who campaign so
fervently against acid rain and lecture their parents about global warming
are also condemned, by well-intentioned consumers and retailers, to wheeze
into inhalers.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    ZAZ  South Africa, Africa.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9651 Regulation of Miscellaneous Commercial Sectors.
    P9511 Air, Water, and Solid Waste Management.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 28
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT944-16106</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EJND7AGMFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941014
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / Survey of International Standards (1): The starting point is
an agreement - It is the voluntary nature of standards that makes them
valuable and workable
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Zigzagging across the South African city of Johannesburg is a reminder of
what can happen when standards differ. The jagged line of Twist Street
commemorates the point at which the two city planners - working inward to
the same grid plan - finally met, about 100 years ago.
The hazards of Twist Street's staggered junctions are due, so the story
goes, to the fact that one builder worked in metres, the other in yards and
inches.
True or apocryphal, it is an example of the problems which are caused for
consumers by the lack of standards.
The starting point of standards has to be an agreement on the physical
measures which are going to be used, a problem which new technologies have
always had to surmount.
Travellers on Britain's early railroads, for example, had to change trains
between different rail tracks, and engines had to be built to different
specifications, until the gauge was nationally agreed by railway engineers
in the nineteenth century at 4ft 8 1/2 in.
In both these cases, those most inconvenienced were the 'consumers' whose
travel times were increased by the absence of a common standard.
More recently, the absence of a common video cassette standard, before the
eventual triumph of the VHS system over its Betamax rival, led to similar
confusion and inconvenience for customers.
The railway example pre-dates the setting up of the International
Organisation for Standardisation (Iso) by more than 100 years.
This is the body which consumers have to thank, with its partner the
International Electrotechnical Commission, for many of the things they take
for granted. These include the ability to plug a standard light bulb into a
socket, (though still in two different formats, screw and bayonet), the
uniform dimensions of leading credit cards used around the world, the
familiar dashboard symbols on cars indicating lights, windscreen wipers,
horn and other equipment, and the conformity of paper sizes.
To the IEC, in particular, goes the credit for harmonising worldwide the
rules for wiring buildings, and attempts, still as yet to reach fruition, to
standardise Europe's electrical plugs and sockets. (Report, Page 4).
Iso has been developing standards since it was founded in 1947 and it has
always operated by consensus. This is of course due to the fact that the
providers of goods and services have more to gain by keeping in line with an
agreed set of standards than they have to lose. The voluntary nature of
standards is also what has made them valuable and workable for consumers,
who are more willing to accept agreed regulations laid down for reasons of
safety or compatibility than rigid external directives which are often seen
as interfering with local custom and supply.
From small beginnings early in this century standards now cover not only the
full range of industrial products and services but newer areas of interest
and concern such as environmental management.
In each case, however, for standards to be accepted and effective, the
working committees of Iso have had to take into account differences in
climate and culture across developing and industrialised countries, and
different structures and overseeing authorities.
There is a reluctance to give up measures that have developed by custom and
culture, and Iso has had to be sensitive to this in order to succeed.
Iso's own name illustrates this. Derived from the Greek word meaning
'equal'. it was chosen because it was considered to be linguistically
neutral and can be used as an international common denominator by Iso
members in 107 countries. The full English title, International Organisation
for Standardisation, is deliberately not an acronym. All standards are
published in English and French and some also in Russian.
Iso has had to be equally impartial in devising a worldwide system for
measurement, a topic which is still the nub of its activities. Since it
published its first standard in 1951 with the title 'Standard reference
temperature for industrial length measurement', it has had to return many
times to a question that arises in many guises: how to create a consensus on
what should be measured, in what way, and to what standard.
The metric system is now enshrined in a 14-part Iso standard covering the
information needed for measurement in just about every field of business,
industry, education, science and technology. At the other end of the scale,
new standards in areas such as environmental management are still being
developed.
World Standards Day is being celebrated today by Iso, the IEC and the
International telecommunications union (ITU) with the slogan 'Standards and
the consumer: partners for a better world.' Its message is designed to
increase awareness of the consumer's part in standards.
'Safety standards protect life and property. Their application creates safer
homes and workplaces, and improves the quality of life for everyone,' the
chief officers of the three organisations argue.
'The net result of industry's use of international standards is a 'level
playing field' on which fair trade and competition can take place, to the
benefit of consumers and society in general.'
Standards, indeed, are doorways that enable goods to enter other countries,
and trade to take place, on equal terms. Japan is notably ready to adapt its
products to world markets.
'When the Japanese design for the world market, they certainly forget
themselves and the very specific needs of their home market,' observes Mr
Bill Moggridge, founder of the design consultancy Ideo.
'As international design consultants we have to come to grips with
international standards. They are a good guide to the burning issues in
safety, functionality, and so on. But we have to move away from standards
that are unfriendly to users but kind to computer chips and connectors. The
process of creating standards still lags behind the way that standards are
actually applied,' Mr Moggridge says.
The IEC, which was created in 1906 has a particular problem because of the
fast-moving nature of the industry in which it operates. However fast it
reacts to technology developments, the computer industry is always going to
be moving faster. The convergence of telephone, fax, computer, copier and
video in multimedia systems has led the IEC, Iso and ITU to warn that 'an
electronic jungle will result unless this exciting rush of developments is
channelled productively by international standards'.
Yet, according to Mr John Kean, vice-president of Iso for technical
management, developments in telecommunications will have the effect of
educating the consumer as never before. Mr Kean gives as an example the
interactive TV available to members of Canacintra, the largest Mexican
chamber of commerce, for industries involved in technological transfer.
'Their 38,000 members can hook into an interactive educational channel,
which deals with issues of manufacture, standards, and procedures. It is a
tool of tremendous potential,' he argues.
Indeed, electronic delivery of standards offers the easiest and swiftest
method yet of publishing and disseminating standards information. Multimedia
and interactive video promise to be seductive educational tools, which makes
international agreement on multimedia standards all the more urgent.
The CD-Rom has already been seized on as an ideal medium by IT experts and
others. CD-Rom is among the formats available from IHS, International
Handling Services, of Englewood, Colorado, which offers a library of the
world's most widely-referenced standards, plus an electronic inquiry
service.
In Britain, IT experts can look up standards on Bits, a PC disc 'Browser'
for IT standards published by the Information Technology Industry Training
Organisation.
Industry experts warn, however, that the electronics and software industries
are racing ahead at such a speed that they are vulnerable to de facto
standards.
These rely entirely on the weight of the user-base, and rarely settle on the
best possible technical solution.
This is a problem which world standards bodies are now having to address.
Despite 100 years or more of standard-making the challenges look like being
no less complex in the next century as an increasingly integrated world
trading environment - heavily dependent on information technology as its
engine - develops apace.
</TEXT>
