<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / Government Bonds: Treasuries surge on lower producer prices
data
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY and MARTIN BRICE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US Treasury bonds surged forward yesterday on news of an unexpected slump in
producer prices last month.
Late in the session, the benchmark 30-year government bond was  23/32 higher
at 96 3/32 , with the yield slipping to 7.833 per cent and the two-year note
was  1/8 better at 99 25/32 , to yield 6.601 per cent.
Although economists had expected yesterday's Labor Department report to
present no obstacle for bonds, few imagined the data would be as favourable
as it proved.
The September producer price index showed a surprising 0.5 per cent decline,
while the 'core' rate, which excludes the more volatile energy and food
sectors, was up by a more modest 0.1 per cent.
Analysts were forecasting a 0.1 per cent rise in the PPI and a 0.4 per cent
increase in core prices. The result in part reflected a 1.1 per cent
downturn in car prices, which were thought to have appreciated.
The inflation-sensitive long end of the maturity range leapt nearly a point
on the news, with speculative retail accounts said to be leading the rally.
Prices receded a little mid-morning, pushed higher just before noon,then
settled back a little late in the day.
The improvement capped a week-long advance for bonds triggered by Friday's
announcement of a much smaller increase in employment in September than
economists had forecast. Yesterday's news reinforced suspicions that the
economy is not accelerating fast enough to warrant an immediate rise in
short-term interest rates by the Federal Reserve.
*something in here (HP) *
However, the news on producer prices failed to chase away all the market's
bearishness. Gains were limited by the reluctance of many traders to make
commitments ahead of today's reports on consumer prices, retail sales and
industrial production.
The consensus forecast of a slight 0.2 per cent gain in consumer prices
appeared to be a safe bet, given the decline at the producer level. The
market was a little more edgy about the level of capacity utilisation at
factories and mines, a good indication of future inflationary trends. The
rate has hovered dangerously near the 85 per cent mark in recent months.
European government bond markets followed the rise in US Treasuries
yesterday, leaving dealers braced for the impact of today's data from the
US.
The US-inspired rally in the UK gilts market prompted the Bank of England to
decide to issue stock into the strength. The Bank said Pounds 200m of 8 1/2
per cent 2007, Pounds 250m of 8 per cent 2013, and Pounds 150m of 2 1/2 per
cent index-linked due 2013 would be available.
News of this long-dated stock led some in the market to expect today's
announcement of auction stock to involve a short-dated issue, possibly a
five-year.
Mr Robert Thomas at NatWest Markets said the tone in the market had been
good. 'Inflation numbers are good and the action by the Bank on interest
rates looks more pre-emptive than it did at the time. People are starting to
say that even if inflation does go up, gilts are still good value.'
The December gilt future on Liffe rose  17/32 to 100 7/8 in late trading.
The yield spread over bunds widened slightly to around 129 in late trading.
German bunds also rose in line with the US. The December bund future was
around 90.29 in late trading, up 0.87 on the day. Mr Thomas Mayer at Goldman
Sachs in Frankfurt said a victory by Chancellor Helmut Kohl in the elections
on Sunday was now firmly priced into the market, and any other result would
come as a shock to bunds.
The Italian government's auction of a total of L5,000bn of bonds in three
tranches was covered between 2.31 and 3.46 times. Mr Corrado Costantino at
Williams de Broe in London said: 'The political situation is so unstable
that I don't think the international investor is willing to put money into
the Italian market.'
