<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / International Capital Markets: Czechoslovak bank loan terms
set benchmark
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICHOLAS DENTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A Czechoslovak bank has broken new ground for east European borrowers by
successfully obtaining a syndicated loan at a spread of less than 100 basis
points over London interbank rate.
A five-year loan of Dollars 50m for Ceskoslovenska Obchodni Banka, the Czech
and Slovak foreign trade bank, has been heavily oversubscribed, arranger
Sumitomo Bank said.
Demand was strong in spite of the most aggressive pricing attempted by an
east European entity, at just 70 basis points above Libor with fees ranging
up to 35 basis points.
Despite initial market concern that the spread was too narrow, Sumitomo Bank
raised Dollars 120m and oversubscription was 140 per cent.
Chase Manhattan Bank, JP Morgan, Lloyds Bank, Midland Bank, Mitsubishi Trust
&amp; Banking Corp, and Tokai Bank joined the syndicate and acted as lead
managers.
Syndicated loan markets have seen an inflow of liquidity which has lowered
spreads for a typical European corporate borrower with a Single A rating
from 45 basis points to as low as 20. In the Czech case, the narrowing has
been faster.
Investors have digested the split of Czechoslovakia, and the Czech
Republic's economic indicators have continued to outperform those of other
former communist countries.
Standard &amp; Poor's, the US rating agency, upgraded the Czech National Bank,
the central bank, to Triple B plus in July this year.
A bond issue by CNB in March 1993, soon after Slovakia became independent,
was sold at a spread of 272 to 278 basis points over comparable US
Treasuries. Spreads fell to 120 basis points over Treasuries in an April
1994 issue by the City of Prague. The CSOB transaction, the first time a
Czech corporation has tapped the syndicated loan market, establishes a new
benchmark.
Other east European borrowers have been drawn to the syndicated loan market
but none has achieved the pricing of the Czech transactions.
Banks heavily oversubscribed a Dollars 100m syndicated loan by InvesTel, the
treasury arm of Hungarian telecommunications company Matav. The deal raised
Dollars 197m and banks were scaled back to Dollars 150m.
</TEXT>
