<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / International Company News: Malaysian Airline seeks to boost
cargo services
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KUALA LUMPUR
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The chairman of troubled Malaysian Airline System (MAS) will soon unveil
plans aimed at cutting costs and generating new business, particularly in
cargo services, officials said, Reuter reports from Kuala Lumpur.
They said Mr Tajudin Ramli would announce alliances with other airlines to
increase flight frequencies, and expand the airline's cargo services. 'The
alliances will increase MAS frequencies to Europe and other regions and also
expand our services,' one official said.
Mr Tajudin, who made his mark in Malaysia's telecommunications sector, has
said previously that he planned to streamline the former state-run airline,
which is south-east Asia's largest carrier.
'MAS is a profitable company and will contribute some 3 per cent to the
Malaysian economy by the year 2000,' Mr Tajudin said yesterday.
He hinted that his plans for the airline focused on the cargo service,
saying it would benefit from Malaysia's rapid industrialisation and
increasing exports.
MAS made a profit of MDollars 8.43m (USDollars 3.29m) on turnover of
MDollars 4.01bn in the last financial year, helped by the sale of old
aircraft. The airline, with a fleet of some 90 aircraft, has also begun
leasing out its excess medium-range aircraft to regional carriers.
</TEXT>
