<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / International Company News: Wallace McCain ousted as head of
frozen food group
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Wallace McCain, 64, has been ousted as co-chief executive of McCain
Foods. His replacement, possibly an outsider, will be appointed soon, writes
Robert Gibbens in Montreal.
However, a bitter, decade-long struggle between Mr Wallace McCain and his
brother, Mr Harrison McCain, 66, over family succession at McCain Foods is
far from over.
Mr Harrison McCain said he would continue as sole chairman and chief
executive until a successor was appointed in the next week or so.
The two brothers have over the past 38 years built McCain Foods into a
frozen foods multinational with annual sales of USDollars 2.5bn. Each
controls 33.57 per cent of the company.
The McCain Foods family-controlled board, after a six-hour meeting in
Toronto, dismissed Mr Wallace McCain and appointed him non-executive
vice-chairman.
Later, he accused his brother of 'playing family politics and keeping the
board under his thumb'. He said he would pursue the lawsuit against his
brother and the company. He maintains that McCain Foods should be
restructured, headed by an outsider, and later taken public.
Mr Harrison McCain said the board's action 'provides a resolution of the
dispute among shareholders and opens the way for an orderly succession of
chief executive'.
Only Mr Wallace McCain's two sons, Scott and Michael, voted against his
dismissal at the board meeting. Neither of the brothers were at the meeting.
</TEXT>
