<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / International Company News: Raytheon reports 22% increase in
profits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Raytheon, the Massa-chusetts-based defence company best known for its
Patriot missile, produced record third-quarter earnings of Dollars 1.45 a
share, an increase of 15 per cent.
On sales up 10 per cent for the quarter at Dollars 2.4bn, operating profits
rose 22 per cent at Dollars 273m. After lower non-operating income, net
profits were up 12 per cent at Dollars 192m. However, the results were seen
as disappointing, and the shares fell Dollars 1 3/4 to close at Dollars 63.
Mr Dennis Picard, chairman, said lower defence spending had led to a fall in
sales and profits in government business. But the non-defence businesses of
engineering, construction, aircraft and appliances all enjoyed a record
third quarter.
The company said that 51 per cent of its Dollars 6.9bn order backlog was
funded by the US government against 65 per cent a year ago. Over that
period, government orders fell 16 per cent and civilian orders rose 50 per
cent. Civilian orders received in the quarter included a Dollars 364m
contract for Acme Steel in Illinois and a Dollars 1bn-plus environmental
surveillance project in Brazil, won in competition with the French defence
group Thomson.
Total debt fell Dollars 350m to Dollars 639m, giving a debt-equity ratio of
14.9 per cent.
Loral, the acquisitive US defence company, produced a 39 per cent gain in
second-quarter earnings per share, or 25 per cent before non-recurring
items. Bernard Schwartz, chairman, said he now expected full-year net income
to rise by more than the previous forecast of 20 per cent, without further
acquisitions or the non-recurring gain.
Sales in the quarter rose 61 per cent to Dollars 1.35bn, reflecting the
acquisition of Federal Systems from January. Net income was up 42 per cent
at Dollars 66.3m, or by 27 per cent before the one-off gain of Dollars 6.9m.
</TEXT>
