<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / International Company News: Record revenues help Whirlpool
to 40% advance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Whirlpool, the US-based maker of washing machines and other home appliances,
saw a strong increase in earnings in its third quarter in spite of the cost
of investing in international expansion.
A big increase in profits from its US operations and a smaller increase in
profits from Europe helped the company report a 40 per cent rise in net
income to Dollars 98m in the three months to September.
This figure included a Dollars 15m gain on the recently-completed sale of
its minority stake in Matsushita Floor Care, a US vacuum cleaner
manufacturer. Leaving aside this and a small restructuring charge in Europe,
net income would have been 20 per cent ahead at Dollars 83m.
Shipment increases in all four of Whirlpool's main markets - North America,
Europe, Latin America and Asia - led to record revenues of Dollars 2.08bn,
up from Dollars 1.91bn last time. Earnings per share were Dollars 1.30, or
Dollars 1.10 excluding the exceptional gain, compared with 96 cents a year
earlier.
In North America, Whirlpool increased its prices in all product categories
and had to absorb further costs associated with the phase-out of
chlorofluorocarbons from refrigerator products. But by maintaining its
market share amid rapidly rising industry shipments, it increased operating
profits from Dollars 120m to Dollars 137m.
In Europe - a big market for Whirlpool since the completion of its Philips
Electronics acquisition three years ago - the company suffered lower margins
because of a shift in the sales mix towards cheaper appliances.
But shipment gains 'significantly better' than the industry average of 2 per
cent helped it achieve profits growth. with the reversal of Dollars
3m-Dollars 4m of warranty reserves now deemed unnecessary, it increased
operating profits from Dollars 40m to Dollars 49m.
Whirlpool added that it was about to announce across-the-board price
increases of about 3 per cent on its European products.
Total earnings from Latin America, though still relatively small, nearly
doubled because of the strong performance of the group's Brazilian
affiliates. Asia produced a 30 per cent increase in revenues but turned in a
loss.
</TEXT>
