<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / International Company News: Murdoch prepares for family
control
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Rupert Murdoch, the News Corporation chairman,is planning to strengthen
the position of his children by ensuring that they will eventually control
all the family interests in the international media group.
The News Corp chairman told the magazine Business Review Weekly that he
planned to buy the 40 per cent of Cruden Investments, the family investment
vehicle, not already held by his immediate family.
Cruden owns about 32 per cent of News Corp - a stake now worth around
ADollars 4.83bn (USDollars 3.55bn).
Mr Murdoch plans to buy the 40 per cent back from members of the extended
Murdoch family over the next five to 10 years, although he declined to say
how this would be financed.
Mr Murdoch, in Australia for News Corp's forthcoming annual meeting, told
Business Review: 'The arrangement is confidential but it will lead to my
children's trusts eventually having 100 per cent of Cruden Investments.'
Although financial problems in recent years have led to a dilution of the
Cruden stake in News Corp, Mr Murdoch has always been keen to retain as much
control as possible and to pass on that control to his children.
He argued in the interview that without an effective controlling family
stake in News Corp, the company could not have been built to its current
size.
Asked which of his two daughters and two sons he would like to succeed him
Mr Murdoch, 63, is quoted as saying: 'I hope we can work it out between us.'
He added, however, that he would probably make a judgment about his
successor in about 20 years.
Mr Murdoch's 23-year-old son Lachlan, who was recently appointed general
manager of News Corp-owned Queensland Newspapers, was present at the
interview. He told the magazine that his father's successor could come from
inside or outside of the family and should be whomever was best for the
company.
Mr Murdoch also defended the controversial plans for a one-for-one issue of
limited voting shares.
'The News Corp shares will do just great and Australian people can buy their
voting shares and the Americans can buy limited-voting shares and get the
bigger dividend,' he said.
Earlier this week Mr Murdoch moved to make the preference shares more
attractive by ensuring that their holders would receive a dividend premium
of at least 20 per cent.
The new shares would also participate on the same basis as the ordinary
shares in any takeover bid for the company.
</TEXT>
