<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / International Company News: Long haul ahead for Canadian
railways - A spate of US mergers has increased pressure on CN and CP
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The harsh realities of the North American transport business are catching up
fast with the Canadian National Railway System.
Hobbled for years by regulators and trade unions, CN is the federal
government's biggest crown corporation and has a reputation as one of
Canada's most bureaucratic organisations.
It lost CDollars 1.1bn (USDollars 820m) between 1991 and 1993 and is weighed
down by debts of almost CDollars 2bn.
However, recent events have cleared the way for the biggest upheaval in CN's
75-year history. Its main rival, the investor-owned Canadian Pacific, has
offered to pay CDollars 1.4bn for CN's rail operations east of Winnipeg and
Chicago.
In response to the CP bid, the government has set up a parliamentary task
force to investigate the 'commercialisation' (privatisation) of CN. The
committee will hold hearings across the country and is due to report before
the end of the year.
In the meantime the two men who will probably play the most decisive role in
deciding CN's future have indicated that they favour radical change.
'The time has come for a decision,' Mr Doug Young, transport minister, said
last month. 'We have to face today's economic realities and ensure that over
the long term CN becomes a competitive and efficient operation.' Mr Paul
Tellier, CN's chief executive, said in a speech earlier this year that 'the
train is still seen as a symbol of our country's glorious past. But we must
focus on measures to develop its full potential.'
The background to the CP offer and the hint of privatisation is CN's
inability to keep pace with the fierce competition and aggressive
cost-cutting which have marked the recent history of North American
railways.
Canadian railways' share of domestic goods traffic has dropped from 70 per
cent to 28 per cent since the early 1960s as more shippers have turned to
road and air transport.
The story is different in the US, where the railways carry more than
two-thirds of the container traffic from the Far East to central Canada, and
have more traffic per kilometre of track and per employee than CN or CP.
They also benefit from more friendly government policies and a more
co-operative workforce. All in all, says Mr Tellier, it costs CDollars
10,000 more to run a train from Vancouver to Toronto than from Seattle to
Chicago.
US railways are far ahead of Canada in adopting more flexible labour
practices, such as switching from three-man to two-man train crews.
Mr James Higgins, analyst at Brown Brothers Harriman in New York, says that
Canada's powerful rail unions and antiquated labour practices are likely to
discourage any US railway from making a bid for either CN or CP.
A spate of mergers among US railways is likely to put even more pressure on
the Canadian companies. In one such move, Conrail and Norfolk Southern are
reported to be negotiating a merger that would form a regional railway
criss-crossing the eastern half of the US. Such an arrangement would worry
the Canadian railways, whose main markets are also in the north-east of the
continent.
The two Canadian companies have launched a series of initiatives in an
attempt to make themselves more attractive to shippers, especially foreign
ones who have a choice between channelling their goods through a US or a
Canadian port.
CN is building a CDollars 200m tunnel under the St Clair River between
Ontario and Michigan which will accommodate double-stack container trains
and cut 12 hours off the journey from Toronto or Montreal to Chicago.
It has also forged marketing and operating alliances with US railways and
trucking companies.
But Mr Tellier has indicated that his top priorities are to improve
productivity and to find a solution for the loss-making eastern Canadian
operations.
Others have begun to question whether Canada can afford the luxury of two
national railways whose lines run virtually side by side in some parts of
the country. CN and CP have lost almost CDollars 2bn combined on their
eastern operations over the past five years.
CN's eastern network contributes about 47 per cent of its revenues, but
almost all its profits come from western Canada, where the bulk goods which
make up most of its traffic - such as coal, grain and sulphur - are less
suited to competition from trucks.
CN's plans have provoked strong opposition from trade unions, which face
extensive job cuts and demands for more flexible work practices. One union
representing more than a third of CN's 23,000 unionised workers is on the
point of calling a strike following a breakdown in contract talks.
CN's railway operations have recently returned to profitability, with
second-quarter net earnings of CDollars 113m. This has led the unions to
claim that the company's problems are largely over, but management counters
that the improvement is due solely to the economic upturn and the company is
still constrained by structural problems.
It will soon be up to the government to choose which side has the stronger
argument.
</TEXT>
