<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / International Company News: JP Morgan profits plunge 30%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JP Morgan, the US bank, reported a 30 per cent slide in third-quarter
after-tax profits from the record level of a year before.
Weaker profits from trading in financial markets, a steep fall-off in
underwriting fees and a loss on foreign government bonds held as investments
were behind the decline.
The fall-off in earnings at JP Morgan, while in line with market
expectations, highlights the continuing difficult trading conditions in
financial markets around the world. The volatile and unexpected price
movements of the first half of the year, particularly in worldwide bond
markets, have given way to thin and erratic trading in more recent months.
Sir Dennis Weatherstone, who steps down as chairman of the US bank at the
end of this year, said market conditions continued to be difficult in the
latest period, but he was pleased with the bank's overall performance.
The biggest dent to JP Morgan's earnings came from a decline in trading
revenues to Dollars 282m from Dollars 464m the year before. This was,
however, an improvement on the Dollars 228m of the second three months of
1994. The greatest contributions to profit came from swaps and bonds,
particularly in the emerging markets. Earlier this year, losses in the
emerging markets had been a significant factor in the decline in trading
profits.
The bank's trading revenues so far this year are running 40 per cent below
their level of 1993, when soaring bond markets bolstered the profits of many
commercial and investment banks.
Movements in the financial markets also led Morgan to report a net
investment loss of Dollars 27m, principally resulting from the sale of
non-US government bonds. A year before, it had reported investment gains of
Dollars 98m.
However, trading in interest-rate instruments added Dollars 73m to the
bank's net interest income, up from Dollars 10m the previous year. Largely
as a result, net interest income was up 20 per cent at Dollars 526m.
The uncertainties in financial markets also hit Morgan's underwriting fees
in the three months to the end of September: these totalled Dollars 22m,
down from Dollars 56m a year before. As a result, corporate finance fees as
a whole dropped by 23 per cent, to Dollars 108m.
Overall, non-interest income dropped by almost a quarter, to Dollars 906m.
With expenses growing by 7 per cent, due largely to higher staffing levels,
the bank's net profits fell to Dollars 327m, or Dollars 1.63 a share, from
Dollars 468m or Dollars 2.30 a year before.
</TEXT>
