<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / International Company News: Metallgesellschaft puts its
defence for futures debacle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW FISHER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
When academics and businessmen lock horns, the clash can be deafening - even
if the dispute is over the esoterica of futures and derivatives.
Attention is virtually guaranteed when the subject is Metallgesellschaft,
the one-time German stock market favourite which almost came to grief this
year as a result of controversial oil dealings.
To defend itself against charges that it mishandled the unwinding of its oil
contracts and precipitated an even bigger loss than might otherwise have
occurred, the industrial and trading company held a press conference on
Wednesday night to put its case.
It said losses on the complex oil contracts - in which derivatives (mostly
futures) were used to hedge long-term fixed price contracts - could have
jeopardised the future of the whole company. It claimed Mr Merton Miller, a
Nobel prize-winning economics professor, and his co-writer, Mr Christopher
Culp (a doctoral candidate at Chicago University), had not grasped how much
of a crisis faced the company.
Mr Michael Hutchinson, managing director of Metallgesellschaft Ltd in the UK
and a member of the risk management team sent to sort out the US problems,
said: 'We're happy with what we've done and will remain happy with what
we've done.' The unwinding was done 'in a way that alleviated the
existence-threatening condition that the massive position had created'.
If the futures contracts entered into by the US oil trading subsidiary (MG
Refining &amp; Marketing) had not been unwound, monthly losses on rolling them
forward would have reached Dollars 50m last December. Contango losses
(caused by futures prices being at a premium over spot prices) alone had
risen to between Dollars 20m and Dollars 30m a month in the last quarter.
The company's oil futures position totalled 180m barrels, more than the 160m
usually quoted, he added. This was equivalent to 85 days of Kuwait's oil
output. Nor were the contango losses offset by any corresponding gains on
MGR&amp;M's futures contracts with customers.
There were further losses of 'hundreds of millions of dollars' through lower
oil prices and consequent margin calls. In New York, Metallgesellschaft said
it paid Dollars 900m in margin calls on oil hedges in 1993. The result of
the debacle was that creditor banks led by Deutsche Bank and Dresdner Bank
mounted a DM3.4bn (Dollars 2.2bn) rescue package to save the company.
Quite how Metallgesellschaft fell into this mess is still unclear. Since it
is the subject of pending legal action, Mr Hutchinson and Mr Hans-Werner
Nolting, the director responsible for trading, said much of the detail had
to stay confidential. They declined to state the size of the present oil
trading position.
The legal wrangle concerns a Dollars 1bn compensation claim by Mr Arthur
Benson, former senior executive at MGR&amp;M, for damage to his reputation
caused by his sacking after the oil losses. Hearings start today in a
Baltimore court on whether this should go to arbitration or be decided in
court.
The nub of the argument by Mr Miller and Mr Culp is that the futures
transactions would eventually have produced profits if they had been kept
going until oil prices rose again. They say, in the draft of an unpublished
article, that a bad situation was made worse by unwinding the contracts too
quickly.
Metallgesellschaft disputes this and says the authors have changed some of
their opinions in a new article out shortly. 'Where Miller and Culp go wrong
is in moving from theory to reality,' said Mr Hutchinson. 'The authors
incorrectly assume that all of MGR&amp;M's long-term supply contracts obligated
the customer to take and pay for at least rateable (in equal amounts)
monthly deliveries.' In fact, a large number of the contracts did not oblige
customers to take any oil products or make payments until almost 10 years
ahead; such flexible contracts running for up to 10 years totalled 50m
barrels.
None of MGR&amp;M's competitors ran 10-year contracts, Mr Nolting said. So when
the full story of how these came about emerges, it should be a fascinating
and salutary saga of how a company supposedly experienced in commodities
trading could come so unstuck. Until then, outsiders can only look on with
bemusement and schadenfreude; investors are left to ponder the value of a
company whose shares languished yesterday at DM163 against DM365 a year ago.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Metallgesellschaft.
</CO>
<XX>
