<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / International Company News: CU spells out its Victoire
strategy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Commercial Union, the UK's largest insurance company, yesterday refused to
rule out job cuts at Groupe Victoire, one of France's largest insurers which
it bought this summer.
Mr Tony Wyand, the new president appointed by CU to Victoire's board, said
he aimed to keep administrative costs as a proportion of turnover on a
continued downward trend.
Mr Wyand indicated that job losses were likely to be in the order of a few
percentage points, and that Victoire was already a 'well-run and efficient
company'.
Mr Bernard Pottier, vice-president, said: 'We will do what proves to be
necessary.' He stressed that the main emphasis was to increase the
connections between different parts of the group.
This would include a reduction in the need for analysts and administrators,
and the imposition of CU's style of monthly reporting, in contrast to the
annual systems in operation at Victoire.
CU revealed that the Victoire name would also become of diminishing
importance, with the holding company for the French operations being
retitled Commercial Union France.
However, Mr Wyand stressed that the subsidiaries would continue to trade
under their existing names, including Abeille Vie and L'Epargne de France.
He said Victoire would probably remain the name for the group's asset
management arm.
The strategy for CU's operations in France would be in line with those of
the group elsewhere: with profitability after tax equivalent to at least 8
per cent on capital invested above inflation.
CU's broader objectives, he said, were to increase the proportion of life
insurance, develop its activities in Europe and improve the quality and
profitability of its casualty business.
The exact price of the CU purchase of Victoire will be determined in
December.
</TEXT>
