<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / UK Company News: David Brown warns on margins
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
David Brown Group, the Yorkshire-based specialist engineer which came to the
market last year, yesterday reported strong growth in sales and exports, but
warned that scope for margin improvement was limited.
The shares, which had fallen steeply ahead of the announcement, closed 13p
up at 213p.
Pre-tax profits rose 22 per cent to Pounds 6.04m for the six months to July
29. Sales grew 59 per cent to Pounds 59.7m - thanks partly to a full
contribution from the hydraulics and transmissions division of Hamworthy,
bought from Powell Duffryn for Pounds 11.1m last November,
Mr Chris Cook, joint chief executive, said margins had been squeezed by
tough trading conditions and the absorption of the less profitable Hamworthy
businesses, although they were now all trading profitably and ahead of
budget.
Mr Cook said the group had responded to the dearth of UK capital projects by
improving its overseas sales and distribution efforts. Partly because of the
Hamworthy deal, the proportion of group sales made overseas increased from
36 to 54 per cent.
Mr Derek Kingsbury, chairman, said: 'With our success in developing export
sales and each of the divisions currentlyshowing an order book higher than
12 months ago, the outlook for sales growth is becoming more encouraging.'
The closure of the Hamworthy plant in Poole, Dorset, involved 170
redundancies, but Mr Cook said he hoped further integration would be
achieved without further job losses.
Vehicle transmissions, the biggest division, showed substantial growth in
sales and operating profit following the integration of the Hamworthy axles
and rail gearbox businesses, together with a strong performance from the
recently developed specialist commercial vehicle activities.
Mr Chris Brown, joint chief executive, said the recent confirmation by the
Ministry of Defence that it would buy a further 259 Challenger 2 tanks from
Vickers meant that David Brown's military products business would be making
transmissions for the tanks until 1999.
Earnings per share rose 3 per cent to 6.7p (6.5p). Mr Cook said the earnings
increase would have been 7 per cent, but for a Pounds 250,000 bad debt
incurred following the collapse of Lancer Boss. The interim dividend is
lifted to 2.25p (2.1p).
</TEXT>
