<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / UK Company News: Abbeycrest reduces loss to Pounds 296,000
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Abbeycrest, the jewellery manufacturer, reduced pre-tax losses from Pounds
345,000 to Pounds 296,000 in the first half of this year and was in the
black at the operating level.
Turnover grew to Pounds 19.2m (Pounds 16.5m), with all sectors of the
group's business increasing sales, and operating profits emerged at Pounds
18,000 (losses Pounds 135,000). Abbeycrest's results are heavily biased
towards the second half.
Losses per share were 0.9p (1p) and the interim dividend is maintained at
1.2p.
Mr Michael Lever, chairman, said he was pleased that last year's progress
had continued, though he added that, as had been the case in previous years,
'it is the next 10 weeks that are crucial to the final result'.
He said that Abbeycrest had lifted its market share in a 'relatively flat,
highly competitive market'.
Margins were maintained, he added, through product strength and marketing
initiatives.
The pre-tax deficit occurred after increased net interest charges of Pounds
314,000 (Pounds 210,000). This rise was as a result of the planned stock
build to improve service in the key pre-Christmas months. There were also
higher infrastructure and management costs, incurred in the drive to lift
operational capability.
Mr Lever said he was convinced that the way to grow was through product
innovation to offset the reduction in demand for jewellery, a result of the
current pressure on consumers' disposable income.
He added that he wanted to further increase the company's market share and
seek new export possibilities.
</TEXT>
