<PROFILE>_AN-EJND7AEOFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941014
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / UK Company News: Allied Domecq sells 641 pubs in Pounds 79m
deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In an unusual deal, Scottish Amicable, the insurer, and the pension fund of
Strathclyde Regional Council, Scotland's biggest local authority, have
together bought 641 pubs from Allied Domecq, the UK food and drinks group,
for Pounds 74.3m.
The pubs are occupied by Pubmaster, the pub retailing arm of the heavily
indebted Brent Walker group, which will continue to lease the properties
from their new owners - but at a reduced rent.
Pubmaster is paying an additional Pounds 4.75m to Allied Domecq - until
recently Allied-Lyons - for the pubs' furniture, fittings and equipment.
Scottish Amicable has bought 75 per cent of the pubs and the rest have been
acquired by Strathclyde's pension fund, which the Glasgow-based insurer
manages.
Pubmaster, which was advised by Lazard Brothers, has been granted a 25-year
lease on the pubs at a substantial cost-saving to the Allied lease. The
agreement also allows Pubmaster to buy one fifth of the pubs every five
years - giving it the opportunity of eventually owning all the freeholds
outright.
Mr John Brackenbury, Pubmaster's chairman, said: 'The terms of the new lease
not only significantly reduce our costs but also give us greater flexibility
to manage our portfolio actively.'
Mr Alan Howie, of Scottish Amicable Investment Managers, said that 'this is
essentially a property transaction offering an index-linked return over 25
years. The deal provides for Pubmaster to continue to manage the portfolio
to the benefit of both parties.'
Mr Tony Trigg, chief executive of Allied Domecq Retailing, said: 'This
agreement is an important move for both parties. Pubmaster is able to secure
the long-term future of this part of the estate. We are able to realise cash
from low-growth assets for reinvestment in our core business.'
Pubmaster has leased the pubs, free of tie, from Allied Domecq since 1992.
Most of them are in the Midlands and the home counties. Pubmaster, which has
a total estate of 1,905 pubs nationally, said the pubs involved in this deal
complemented its existing strengths in the north and north-east of England.
Mr David Hunter, head of property investment at Scottish Amicable, said the
investment was underpinned by the vacant possession valuation of the
portfolio.
Pubmaster, launched in 1991, has become the UK's biggest independent pub
retailer through buying pubs from brewers such as Allied, Whitbread and
Bass, which were required to reduce the size of their estates by the
Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
</TEXT>
