<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / UK Company News: RJB may launch public offer - Pounds 1bn
cost of British Coal business will partly be met by share issue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WIGHTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RJB Mining is likely to use bank debt to fund more than half the total
Pounds 1bn cost of taking over British Coal's English mining assets. That
could leave more than Pounds 400m to be raised from a share issue, which is
expected to include a public offer for sale.
RJB, which the government declared on Wednesday was its preferred bidder for
British Coal's three English regions, was financially one the strongest of
the contenders. However, following the temporary suspension of its shares
ahead of the announcement, it has a market value of less than Pounds 160m.
Even so, it persuaded NM Rothschild, the government's advisers, that it
would be able to raise the Pounds 1bn.
The nature of the British Coal business should mean that reasonably cheap
bank debt will not be too hard to find, while RJB has a strong shareholder
base to support a large equity issue.
RJB and its adviser, Barclays de Zoete Wedd, would not comment on the
details of the proposed financing but it is thought likely that over half
the funding will be provided by bank debt arranged by Barclays Mining
Finance.
'Banks are falling over themselves to lend at the moment and the cash flow
profile of the British Coal business should make it quite an attractive
proposition. RJB has already shown it can turn around former British Coal
pits quite quickly,' said one analyst.
Although it is unclear what asset value the British Coal pits would be given
in the enlarged group's books, it is likely to start life highly geared.
However, the British Coal businesses come with supply contracts with the
electricity generators lasting until March 1998. Assuming that RJB can keep
costs under control, this should guarantee at least three years of strong
cash flow, which could be used to pay down a large part of the bank debt.
RJB is thought to have offered the government about Pounds 900m for the
British Coal assets and will need to raise at least another Pounds 100m to
fund working capital and pay the transaction expenses.
Somewhat less than half the total cost is expected to be met by a share
issue. When RJB came to the market in June last year there was a poor
response from the public, with most of the shares going to institutional
investors. But it has since performed well and subsequent share placings
have given it a solid investor base.
Its leading shareholders include Mercury Asset Management, Prolific, Norwich
Union, Scottish Widows, Henderson and Abbey Life.
Institutions will have acquired the shares in the knowledge that a
successful British Coal bid would require a substantial equity issue and
Rothschild will have satisfied itself that the existing investors would
support one. It is likely to include an offer for sale, which would allow
RJB to bring in new institutional investors and give former British Coal
employees and the public the opportunity to buy shares.
Given British Coal's record, the issue will take some marketing; with the
government hoping to have everything wrapped up by Christmas, the timetable
is tight.
</TEXT>
