<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / Microsoft in Dollars 1.5bn purchase of Intuit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Microsoft, the world's largest computer software company, has agreed to
acquire Intuit, publisher of a widely-used personal financial planning
program for personal computers, for about Dollars 1.5bn in stock.
California-based Intuit is a developer of personal finance, small business
accounting and tax preparation software. Intuit's Quicken software enables
users to manage their personal and small business finances.
The companies said that the deal had been agreed by their respective boards.
Under the terms of the agreement, each Intuit share will be exchanged for
1.336 Microsoft shares, with an adjustment designed to ensure a value to
Intuit shareholders of at least Dollars 71 per Intuit share.
Microsoft said it expected to issue a total of about 27m common shares to
pay for the deal. This represents just under 5 per cent of its outstanding
shares.
'We believe that as part of Microsoft we will more quickly advance toward
our goal of improving people's financial lives and helping financial
institutions use the information highway for closer, richer relationships
with their customers,' said Mr Scott Cook, Intuit chairman.
Mr Cook will become responsible for Microsoft's business in the personal
finance sector.
'Scott and I share a vision of how technology can enable people to execute
financial transactions and make informed decisions more quickly,' added Mr
Bill Gates, Microsoft chairman.
Personal finance is one of the few segments of the PC software market in
which Microsoft is not a market leader. Microsoft's Money program, which
competes with Quicken, has not been a big seller, in spite of collaborative
agreements with several large banks that link the program to their
personal-computer home banking services.
To avoid potential anti-trust problems, Microsoft has agreed to divest its
existing personal finance product, called Money. It will be sold to Novell,
although the terms have not been disclosed.
The Microsoft-Intuit agreement was announced after the close of trading
yesterday. Shares of Intuit had gained Dollars 3 1/4 to Dollars 50 1/4
yesterday before trading was halted. Microsoft closed at Dollars 57 1/4, up
Dollars 1.
</TEXT>
