<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / Aerostructures plans new profit warning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON and BERNARD GRAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Aerostructures Hamble, the aircraft components company, will warn today that
its profits both this year and next will be well below its expectations when
came to the stock market in June, because of a combination of production
difficulties and order deferrals.
The resignation of Mr Andrew Barr, Aerostructures' chief executive, who
realised Pounds 1.74m from the sale of shares in the flotation, will also be
announced. Mr Barr is understood to be unwell. He will be replaced
temporarily by Mr David Ring, the commercial director, until a permanent
replacement is found.
In an attempt to placate shareholders, who are furious that no details of
these problems were contained in the flotation prospectus, a precise
timetable of when the financial difficulties came to light will be
published.
The company will say that non-executive directors, led by chairman Lord
King, former British Airways chairman, had no knowledge of the problems
until a board meeting in mid-September. The non-executives then informed NM
Rothschild, the merchant bank which brought Aerostructures to the market.
Rothschild passed the bad news to Aerostructures's auditors, Coopers &amp;
Lybrand, its stockbrokers, Smith New Court, and Ashurst Morris Crisp,
solicitors to the flotation. Shareholders were not told until September 21.
Today's statement will say Aerostructures's executives first became aware of
production difficulties in the middle of July, but the financial
implications were not apparent to them. By the middle of August, they began
to realise the difficulties could have an adverse effect on results.
The delay of several weeks in informing the full board was a combination of
'bad luck and bad judgment', according to a company employee with a close
knowledge of the report.
However, Hamble's shareholders, led by Abbey Life and Henderson
Administration, are likely to become even more angry when they learn that
the company's prospects in 1995 have deteriorated, because substantial
orders have been deferred.
Although Aerostructures is expected to make a profit in 1994, the outlook
for 1995 is understood to be less certain.
The prospectus said 'market conditions' in 1994 were 'broadly similar to
1993'. It said action had been taken to make 'operational cost savings' so
that profit margins would be better than in 1993. It said: 'Accordingly, the
directors are confident about the prospects for the year'. There was also an
optimistic statement about future growth. As a result, Rothschild is
expecting to face a barrage of criticism from shareholders in coming weeks.
Aerostructures was floated at 120p, valuing the company at Pounds 57m. Its
share price, which fell sharply on September 21, closed yesterday at 59p.
The quality of components supplied by Aerostructures had been a concern to
British Aerospace, its biggest customer, since the late spring, according to
defence executives with a close knowledge of both companies. BAe seconded
several engineers to Aerostructures in May to try to rectify problems before
they had an impact on BAe equipment.
The difficulties proved worse than BAe initially expected. BAe now has 48
engineers at Hamble working on quality control problems affecting rear
fuselages of Hawk and Harrier fighter aircraft, which Aerostructures makes
for BAe. BAe has the capacity to take the manufacturing back to its own
plant, but has decided not to do so.
</TEXT>
