<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / Partners sought to take Bull by horns: The French computer
group faces a tough task
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
When Mr Jean-Marie Descarpentries was appointed chairman of Groupe Bull last
October, he was presented with a life or death battle. The French computer
manufacturer which had racked up losses of more than FFr15bn (Pounds 1.8bn)
over the past three years, a feat rivalled only by Air France and Credit
Lyonnais - the two other black holes of the French public sector.
Since his arrival, he has launched a restructuring plan aimed at stemming
losses, redressing Bull's battered reputation and finding a path to the
private sector.
A vital condition for his mission has been what he describes as a 'one-time,
last-time' capital injection to eliminate the group's debt burden. Thus,
Wednesday's decision by the European Commission to approve capital increases
totalling FFr11.1bn represents a significant step in Mr Descarpentries'
recovery plan.
It is testimony to the task confronting Bull, however, that the capital
increase is a necessary, but not sufficient, condition of survival. Despite
the award of the capital increase, Bull still faces a tough task in proving
it can get back on course, and that it can entice industry partners
necessary for long-term security.
There is much at stake. Bull is one of Europe's few remaining computer
manufacturers and a symbol of France's determination to maintain a presence
in the increasingly competitive sector.
For Mr Descarpentries, failure is now firmly off the agenda. He predicts
that after a net loss of FFr5.07bn in 1993, the group will break even at the
operating level by the end of this year, and at the net level in 1995.
Such ambitious objectives are based on the chairman's battle plan. He has
implemented a series of cost-cutting measures, reducing Bull's Paris sites
from 25 to five, disposing of non-core assets, and accelerating a plan to
cut 6,500 jobs in 1993 and 1994.
Equally important, however, has been the reorganisation of the management
structure. Mr Descarpentries has broken Bull into profit centres, with seven
product/service divisions and four geographic networks. The new
organisation, aimed at tightening notoriously lax reporting procedures, is
controlled by a 10-member management board, selected by the new chairman.
In so doing, Mr Descarpentries has sought to remedy the structural
weaknesses of the group which, along with the fierce price competition in
the computer industry, prompted Bull's decline. As Mr Gerard Longuet, the
French industry minister, said at the time of Mr Descarpentries'
appointment: 'Since its nationalisation in 1982, Bull has been too dependent
on the state and too inflexible. This has undermined its ability to respond
to the upheavals in its markets.'
Mr Longuet now takes a more optimistic line. 'Bull is on the road to
recovery,' he claims. His view is endorsed by the European Commission, which
says Mr Descarpentries' achievements help justify the approval of the
capital increase.
These encouraging sentiments are buttressed by signs of improvement at the
bottom line. Losses in the first half of this year were more than halved to
FFr843m, compared with FFr1.98bn in the comparable period in 1993. Zenith
Data Systems, the personal computer division which has been one of Bull's
principal sources of losses since its acquisition in 1989, is also on the
mend.
But despite Bull's progress, important questions remain about the group's
strategy and its ability to forge the alliances necessary to secure its
position in the international industry. As one computer industry analyst
puts it: 'Cost-cutting takes you only so far. Bull does not have the
international scale to feel secure in the industry. That is important
because the shake-out in the industry is far from over.'
This sentiment was echoed by an independent audit ordered by the Commission.
The report argued that that privatisation and the formation of industrial
alliances is essential for Bull's future. 'This operation must start as soon
as possible . . . an agreement with new shareholders must be found, if not
finalised, between now and June 1995,' claims the report. It argues that the
status quo is not an option.
The message is not lost on Mr Descarpentries, who has concluded a series of
strategic alliances to strengthen Bull's operations. Since the beginning of
last month, the French group announced separate alliances with Tandem,
Motorola and Wang of the US.
The problem, however, is that Bull is in pressing need of partners to
replace the French state on the shareholder register. Officials at the
industry ministry and at the company say that negotiations are proceeding
well with potential investors, while the government expects to launch a
tender offer within the next few weeks. The aim is to reduce the
government's 76 per cent holding to a minority before next spring's
presidential elections.
Bull's improving results render the company a more attractive proposition,
but investors will take some persuading. IBM, which holds 2.1 per cent of
Bull's shares, appears unwilling to be wooed. The US group has said it will
continue to co-operate with Bull in areas such as reduced instruction set
computing (Risc) microprocessor technology.
But it declined to participate in last year's capital increase. More
probable is that NEC of Japan, which holds 4.4 per cent of Bull, and which
co-develops mainframe computers with the French company, will raise its
holding.
Not surprisingly, the Bull chairman and his state shareholders argue that it
is speed rather than nationality which is the priority. This represents a
contrast from the situation in 1991, when Mrs Edith Cresson, then Socialist
premier, opposed NEC's investment in Bull. The change in stance partly
reflects a more liberal attitude by the centre-right government. But the
principal difference is the urgency of Bull's need.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Groupe Bull.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>FRZ  France, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3571 Electronic Computers.
    P3577 Computer Peripheral Equipment, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
