<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / Japan's big banks enter securities markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GERARD BAKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Japanese Ministry of Finance has given the go-ahead for five leading
Japanese commercial banks to move into the securities markets.
Their arrival next month will represent one of the most substantial
shake-ups in the history of Japan's financial system.
The ministry announced yesterday that it had accepted the final details of
the banks' plans to establish securities subsidiaries, as part of the
continuing liberalisation of Japan's rigidly regulated financial system.
The five banks - Dai-Ichi Kangyo, Fuji, Sanwa, Sakura and Mitsubishi - will
establish units next month each backed by capital of about Y40bn (Pounds
253m) and employing up to 120 staff.
The world's largest bank, Sumitomo, failed to win approval because of a
disagreement with regulators over the name of its planned subsidiary.
Japan previously strictly segregated banks and securities companies along
the lines of the US Glass-Steagall Act. The ministry, mindful of the threat
that the new brokerages represent to existing brokers, has, for the time
being at least, limited the scope of their activities.
They are not permitted to compete in the main area of securities business -
equity trading - and there must be strict 'fire walls' between the parent
companies and their offshoots. The banks' units will be restricted to
corporate bond issuance.
Details, Page 4
See Lex
</TEXT>
