<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / The Lex Column: Body Shop
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
There was little to complain about in yesterday's figures from Body Shop.
The adverse publicity which has swirled around the group this summer has had
no perceptible impact on sales. The decline in like-for-like turnover in the
UK, a feature of the results in 1992-93, has been arrested. The expansion of
the retail network continues apace, especially in Asia where sales were up
46 per cent in total and 91 per cent ahead in Japan alone. Despite all the
worries that surround one of the last 80s go-go stocks still to be going,
the Body Shop formula seems to be in good order. The number of shops
operated around the world should rise from 1,136 now to at least 2,000 by
the end of the century.
Two doubts remain. The first is the US, where Body Shop, on its own
admission, has a weak market position reflected in a 1 per cent drop in
like-for-like sales in the first half. Body Shop is hoping to tackle this
with intensified marketing and advertising. The second problem is mounting
competition in the UK. Today the first Bath &amp; Body Works opens, a joint
venture between The Limited, a powerful US retail group, and Next. Over five
years this may pose a serious threat. In the short term, though, Body Shop's
earnings momentum will not be endangered and the shares' premium rating
seems justified.
</TEXT>
