<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / The Lex Column: Cadbury Schweppes
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The near 3 per cent drop in Cadbury Schweppes' share price against
yesterday's buoyant market trend must be galling for the company which last
month announced the best interim results in the food manufacturing sector.
It is especially so when Tesco's agreement to market Virgin Cola - the
immediate trigger to the share price fall - poses a minimal direct threat to
Cadbury's profits. Only 4 to 5 per cent of total group earnings derives from
soft drinks sold in UK supermarkets. Of that a fraction is Coca-Cola sold in
Tesco.
But the link between Tesco and Virgin, which will lend its name to a drink
brewed by the Canadian Cott Corporation, is symptomatic of change in the
balance of power between retailers and food manufacturers. Supermarkets'
private label products have gained ground at the expense of traditional
brands, skewering manufacturers' margins. Until recently one segment of the
market which has resisted the threat has been soft drinks, where the own
label share of the market rose modestly from 28 to 33 per cent between 1980
and 1993. However J. Sainsbury's launch of its Classic Cola earlier this
year turned the tables against the manufacturers. Tesco's link with Virgin
Cola is a further assault on the plump margins earned by Coca-Cola &amp;
Schweppes Beverages.
To a large extent, the share price reaction reflects sentiment rather than
fundamentals. But that sentiment is understandable - the Cola wars may
spread spread beyond the supermarkets. The Tesco/Virgin deal is the thin end
of an unpleasant wedge for Cadbury.
</TEXT>
