<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / Further cracks in emperor's image: Robert Graham discusses
whether the Berlusconi government in Italy is likely to survive the latest
blows
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Five months into office, and the Berlusconi government has already acquired
the air of a lame-duck administration. Through inexperience and poor
judgment, Silvio Berlusconi, the media magnate turned premier, has scored a
string of own goals, which have brought his own future and the durability of
his government into question.
He has become involved in a bruising battle with the judiciary over
corruption investigations into his Fininvest business empire, in which
something has to give - with the threat of his implication the stuff of
every newspaper's front page for the past two weeks.
He has failed to find a quick solution to the conflict of interest between
his role as head of government and his ownership of Italy's second largest
private business group. And his nerve in introducing much-needed reforms is
due to be tested today by a four-hour general strike in protest at cuts in
pension and healthcare benefits in the 1995 budget.
The unions organised similar general strikes against the two previous
budgets, of the Amato and Ciampi governments, and Mr Berlusconi has
dismissed today's protest as 'a ritual performance to reassert their
presence and identity'.
But this time there is a genuine sense of confrontation, with the pensions
issue affecting a large cross-section of the electorate.
The government has failed to communicate the genuine urgency of tackling the
pensions issue and confused people by frequent changes in the detail of the
proposal. Many are worried they will lose out, or simply do not know their
status. This is evident both in street conversations as well as in the
responses to hotlines run by the newspapers and government.
Those who know Mr Berlusconi well say he has failed in his usually
successful role as a communicator, because he has a visceral distaste of
communicating bad news. He has only begun to talk of the need for
'sacrifices' in the past two weeks, and this in low key.
'We get the feeling Berlusconi changed tactics at the last minute and sought
a confrontation with us which he always said he wanted to avoid,' comments
one senior trade unionist.
Certainly the government was bending over backwards to accommodate the
unions until Mr Giovanni Agnelli, chairman of Fiat and an arbiter of
business opinion, called in Mr Berlusconi for an informal dinner, dubbed
'the last supper', on September 23. Mr Berlusconi is believed to have been
told that without a tough budget his government stood no chance of winning
international credibility, let alone of retaining the continuing support of
the business community that he claims to represent. From this point on, the
government's position toughened and the 1995 budget presented a courageous
attempt to reform the money-devouring pay-as-you-go state pensions system.
Italy will now accelerate the pace at which it moves to fix the male
retirement age at 65 and the female at 60; early retirement will be
penalised; the rate at which pensions accrue will be cut and private schemes
will be encouraged.
No one disputes the need for these changes. The markets, in particular, are
worried about Italy's budget deficit and mountain of debt. Treasury funding
of the pensions deficit will be almost L85,000bn (Pounds 34bn) this year
and, if unchecked, will play havoc with Italy's future financial stability.
Indeed, having courted unpopularity in the budget, it is arguable that Mr
Berlusconi should have been more ambitious in his aims. In 1993, the Amato
government found almost double the L50,000bn being sought by Mr Berlusconi
in new revenues and spending cuts.
Even if the general strike passes off quietly, the government will only have
won a breathing space for Italy's public finances. Similar, perhaps larger
sums will have to be found to keep the budget deficit from rising above 8
per cent of gross domestic product again in 1996.
But as a leader, Mr Berlusconi has failed to impose his authority on the
cabinet. He swings between listening to the hawkish advice of those such as
Mr Giuliano Ferrara, the minister for parliamentary affairs, and Mr Cesare
Previti, his Fininvest lawyer and now defence minister, and listening to the
more cautious counsel of his other colleagues. The hawks have pushed him
into frequent clashes with President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro, which he has
invariably lost.
Mr Berlusconi is also proving thin-skinned. He reacts defensively even to
constructive criticism and sees conspiracies against him everywhere, not
least in the local and foreign press. He complains openly about how hard he
has to work, as if the country were ungrateful for his personal sacrifice.
'The quality of my life has deteriorated since I took on this job,' he said
this week, adding: 'I work 16 to 18 hours a day.'
While these faults could be put down to inexperience, others are seemingly
irremediable. These derive from Mr Berlusconi having entered politics
without clearing his position with the judiciary over corruption
investigations into Fininvest and without distancing himself properly from
his ownership of Fininvest.
As a result, he has been weakened by continual conflicts of interest. The
worst involves the government shake-up of the RAI, the state broadcasting
organisation, which risks being beneficial to his own three commercial
channels. Only at the last minute, on President Scalfaro's insistence, was
legislation removed from the 1995 budget that raised the RAI's annual
operating fee and left that of Fininvest untouched.
This week the senate began to debate proposals drawn up by three
Berlusconi-appointed jurists on ways to avoid a conflict of interest. Mr
Berlusconi has promised that legislation based on the jurists' ideas will be
considered by the next cabinet. However, Fininvest is deeply rooted in the
government, having provided three ministers plus the funds and organisation
for Forza Italia, Mr Berlusconi's support movement. In addition, any
solution to the conflict of interest is likely to be slow and partial
because Fininvest is so big and so indebted.
Mr Berlusconi also now finds himself in open conflict with Milan magistrates
and their colleagues in Rome and Turin, who are pursuing separate inquiries
into Fininvest affairs. The most damaging investigation is into allegations
of bribing the Guardia di Finanza, the financial police, to turn a blind eye
to the true ownership of Telepiu, the cable TV channel in which Fininvest
has a declared 10 per cent stake.
Mr Francesco Saverio Borrelli, the Milan public prosecutor, in a serious
breach of his judicial role publicly warned last week that the net of
investigation was closing round Mr Berlusconi. The magistrates cannot go on
playing a cat and mouse game with the prime minister. Equally, given the
continued popularity of the magistrates, it will be hard for the government
to head them off.
For Mr Berlusconi's main coalition partners - the populist Northern League
of Mr Umberto Bossi, and the neo-fascist MSI/National Alliance, headed by Mr
Gianfranco Fini - this has proved reason enough to begin manoeuvring
themselves for Mr Berlusconi's departure as prime minister. If he were to
go, they calculate that Forza Italia would collapse as it has no rationale
other than to back the prime minister.
Mr Fini is making himself more attractive by pushing the uglier elements in
his movement to one side. Simultaneously he is wooing, with considerable
success, Forza Italia support in southern Italy. However, he is unlikely to
do anything to prejudice the existence of the government as long as Mr
Berlusconi stays. Mr Bossi, on the other hand, has always been uncomfortable
in the coalition and will pull out whenever it suits him. He is already
emphasising the League's separate identity, and testing new alliances in the
centre and on the left.
The opposition has not really shown its hand. The main group, the former
communist Party of the Democratic Left (PDS), is still adjusting to the new
leadership of Mr Massimo D'Alema after the angry resignation of Mr Achille
Occhetto in the wake of its defeat in the March general elections.
But, tactically, the PDS wants to see the Berlusconi government thoroughly
discredited so as to avoid the reshaping or enlargement of the rightwing
coalition. The party is against early elections, preferring to wait for a
further refinement of the 1993 electoral laws that introduced the
first-past-the-post system - a view shared by all the political parties. The
need to change the electoral law also limits Mr Berlusconi's ability to go
to the country with a snap election.
The situation is thus profoundly unstable and uncertain. If Mr Berlusconi
now faces a limited tenure, he has no one but himself to blame. He has
squandered a huge groundswell of popular support, alienated sympathetic
investors and, if he is not careful, could damage Italy's economic recovery,
which looks stronger every day.
</TEXT>
