<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / Leading Article: The choices for Germany
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The outcome of Sunday's German general election will have an impact well
beyond Germany's borders. Europe's pivotal nation has the chance of using
the next four years both to put its economic house in order and to prepare
the European Union for a decisive phase of enlargement at the beginning of
the next century.
The next German government should set itself three prime objectives: to
improve the country's economic structure; to narrow the gap between east and
west Germans; and to make Germany a more effective proponent of European
integration.
Pressing attention needs to be given to public finances. In spite of this
year's faster than expected recovery, public spending and revenue as a
proportion of gross domestic product will be 5 per cent higher next year
than before unification. By the end of this year public debt will have
doubled since 1990. The next government will have to make further cuts in
spending, including on welfare benefits. It will also have to maintain
efforts to encourage labour flexibility and to reduce state interference in
the economy.
Net public sector transfers to east Germany should fall gradually from now
on. But east Germany will hardly come close to matching overall economic
performance in the west for another 15 years. The next government needs
somehow to infuse east and west Germans with a sense of their joint
responsibility in over-coming the legacy of 40 years' division.
Kohl's belief
Though often vague and indecisive about details, the incumbent chancellor,
Helmut Kohl, deserves credit for sticking to one fundamental belief: that
the unification of Germany must be carried out within the wider context of
Europe. The difficulties involved in the process have caused some ebbing of
German support for his vision, but Mr Kohl himself is unlikely to abandon
it.
If still in power after October 16 he may have to be more cautious about
urging an extension of supranational European decision-making, in deference
both to German public opinion and to his European partners. But neither he
nor any successor is likely to abandon the priority of opening the Union to
central and eastern Europe, so that the inevitable expansion of German
influence there can occur as part of a wider integration process.
So Germany will have to be more strenuous than ever in advocating reform of
the Common Agricultural Policy, the structural funds, and the Union's
decision-making machinery. It will also have to be prepared to play a full
part in common European defence arrangements, which means overcoming the
remaining inhibitions about deploying German soldiers as part of
multinational forces outside the Nato area.
Gargantuan tasks
All these policies are likely to be espoused most readily if Mr Kohl remains
in power, and continues his alliance with the liberal Free Democrats. That
is the outcome which most of Germany's foreign partners will be hoping for.
The only doubt is whether Mr Kohl and his colleagues, after so many years in
office, still have the stamina required for such gargantuan tasks.
A coalition of Social Democrats and Greens is less likely - and would be
less well-equipped to tackle Germany's pressing economic problems. A more
likely outcome is that the FDP will fall short of the 5 per cent threshold
required for representation in the Bundestag, with the result that Mr Kohl
has to form a 'grand coalition' with the SPD.
Such a coalition might have greater difficulty in agreeing on policies than
the present one, but it could be better placed to implement them once it had
done so, especially as it would not have to fear a veto on its tax
legislation from the SPD majority in the Bundesrat (federal council). It
would also have great pedagogic value for the SPD, which, like other social
democratic parties, finds it easier to adjust to unwelcome realities in
office than in opposition. In the 1960s such a grand coalition provided a
three-year transitional phase before the SPD took over the leadership of the
country in 1969. The return of the present coalition led by a re-energised
Mr Kohl would be the best outcome: but a grand coalition would not signal a
fundamental change of course.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>DEZ  Germany, EC.
