<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / Letters to the Editor: Efficient - but wrong
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr MIKE PARR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Mr David Henderson and Mr David Sawers (Letters, October 12) make the
usual mistake of confusing efficiency with effectiveness. The efficient
allocation of resources by UK corporations has led to no indigenous UK car
industry, motorcycle industry or computer industry, a semiconductor industry
on its last legs and a declining industrial base. The UK's European
competitors make this error less often, one of the reasons they are better
off and the UK is now the poor man of Europe.
The application of rationalism to every investment decision (efficiency
above all]) has given rise to the above.
It is unlikely that UK helicopter component manufacturers are any worse or
better in terms of 'efficiency' than their competitors. Thus, the arguments
concerning a 'waste of resources' are fallacious.
Second, generally speaking, items with added value that comes from thought
(helicopters) command a higher price in the market for a given unit of
effort than those that need muscle (coal). Thus, the production of high-tech
products should lead to a wealthier population. I think the Singaporeans
have conclusively proved this.
Efficiency has its place, but don't forget that it is entirely possible
efficiently to do the wrong thing. This is usually avoided by applying
common sense.
Mike Parr,
69 Avenue General Medecin Derache,
1050 Ixelles,
Brussels, Belgium
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>BEZ  Belgium, EC.
