<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / A vote on Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOE ROGALY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major could show himself to be the cleverest bastard of them all
today. 'Bastard', you may recall, is the term the prime minister once
famously used to describe the uppity liberal nationalists within his
administration. Several of his superficially loyal lib-nat colleagues have
cast doubt on their own legitimacy this week. They have paid lip service to
the government's carefully constructed position on the development of the
European Union, but their body language has indicated that they do not
believe a word of it. Mr Major could outflank them. He could promise a
referendum on Europe.
Let me explain. All politicians can learn from the speech given by Mr Tony
Blair at the eau-de-nil conference in Blackpool 10 days ago. The Labour
leader painted a picture of where he wanted to take the country. He sounded
honest and straightforward. He capped his peroration with a sizzler. By
undertaking to review the party's constitution, simultaneously translated by
his aides to mean abandoning the socialist Clause 4, Mr Blair convinced his
audience, including some Conservative observers, that he had the stuff of
leadership in him. The honest and straightforward Mr Major could have the
equivalent effect today.
When he addresses the Conservative conference in Bournemouth this afternoon
the prime minister will presumably stick by his European strategy, which is
increasingly Gaullist. Beyond that he could, if he chose, say that his
government would consult the people before throwing sterling into the
melting pot of a single European currency. Monetary union may never happen,
but, he could intimate, if it does Britain's position will be decided by the
electorate. Mr Major's minions could fan out among the media and, nudge
nudge, explain that by 'consult the people' he means a referendum.
There is one immediate snag. The prime minister has repeatedly declared his
opposition to plebiscites, on the ground that decisions should be taken in
Parliament. Against that, he has just conceded a popular vote on the future
of Northern Ireland. It is to his credit that he has done so. His careful
management of the peace process is evidence of how his painstaking attention
to detail, allied to his negotiating skills, can best be deployed. The
declaration signed by Mr Major and his Irish counterpart at Downing Street
before Christmas tied every participant - British, Irish, Northern Irish -
to the principle of self-determination. That alone was worth establishing.
The ceasefire announced by the 'loyalist' terrorists yesterday is evidence
of the declaration's powerful effect.
There is, however, a corollary. Self-determination cannot reasonably be
granted to Ulster and subsequently denied the rest of the country. I have
long argued that the EU is not an embryonic federation, but a casbah of
governments, a permanent session of bargaining among national states. That
proposition could not be sustained if the members of the EU melded their
currencies and placed the management of their economies under the control of
a single central bank. It would be a constitutional leap in the dark of
greater importance than the matter of whether there is a united Ireland or a
self-governing Scotland. Given the prospect of such a tremendous change in
our fortunes, a referendum would be more than politic. It would be right.
Opponents of a national vote always ask what the question would be. This one
is easy. 'Do you want to join the European single currency?' A Yes and we
would be in; a No and we would remain outside. The national debate that
would precede the voting might be more elevated than cynics expect. A
promise that such a question will be asked if the time comes should unite
the Conservatives. It could silence most of the nationalist faction within
the party. It would pre-empt an almost certain decision by Labour to promise
a similar plebiscite if they are el-ected. It might even attract voters'
attention.
Fanatical chauvinists may protest that this is not enough. A referendum in
the wild blue yonder, following, say, the amalgamation of the French franc,
the D-Mark and the Benelux currencies, is too far away, too uncertain. They
want a vote in principle, now. More ambitiously, they want the question to
be 'do you want a federal Europe?' hoping for a No. That would pre-empt what
they fear will be a further erosion of sovereignty following the 1996
inter-governmental conference on the development of the EU. On such matters
the Eurosceptics are, however, divided, the wildest of them postulating a
withdrawal from the Union. They are fighting under their blankets, each
clutching their own nightmare.
Those who would not quieten down after an offer of a single-currency
referendum could, for a while at least, be ignored. Ministers I have spoken
with in Bournemouth show some nervousness about what may be a close vote on
the forthcoming 'own resources' bill on the finances of the EU. Are the
backbench bastards hoping to bring the government down so that they might
capture the party while in opposition? Is Mr Michael Quixote the potential
leader of such a coup? I doubt it. On past form, the schismatics, themselves
divided, will use the tension surrounding the passage of the own resources
bill to extract such sceptical statements as they can from the prime
minister. They picture themselves squeezing Mr Major to the last available
drop, then supporting the government.
Nobody expects the prime minister to announce a referendum this afternoon.
It will be surprising if he does. Yet it is likely that by the time of the
next election all three national parties will be committed to a popular vote
on the EU. The Liberal Democrats are already there, Labour within a whisker
of a decision. As to the outcome, senior ministers I consulted agree that
Britain would probably stay out of a single currency at the start, then,
after a few years, scramble to get in. One, a sceptic who thinks joining a
single currency wrong on principle, accepts that, if the continental
countries create a monetary union that works, we might think again. The
chancellor says 'one day'; others 'never'.
Come to think of it, we may need two plebiscites on a single currency before
the decade is out, the first to say No and the second Yes.
</TEXT>
<XX>
