<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tomorrow's World has always been a gee-whiz programme appealing particularly
to children, but one characteristic made it attractive to anyone interested
in broadcasting: it was presented live. This meant fizz and adrenalin, and
that things could, and did, go wrong, a fact which could pull you in whether
or not you were interested in widgets. Now, after nearly 30 years, they have
finally chickened out and decided that, like everyone else, they will have a
little collection of pre-packaged filmlets. Safety at last - but for me not
worth watching any more (7.30 BBC1). Second Thoughts reaches its last
episode without ever having impinged upon me more than incidentally:
whenever I caught sight I thought 'Oh another sitcom about people not
married to one another trying to live together'. Since it never passed the
test of making me laugh within three minutes of switching on I never watched
a whole episode (8.30 ITV). Conversely, anything starring Alexei Sayle
receives instant attention. Paris is a new comedy series in which he plays
French artist Alain Degout in the 1920s (9.30 C4).
</TEXT>
