<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / Arts: What a Performance - Theatre
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL DRIVER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Some things pass away forever, leaving not a wrack nor even a half-way
decent video behind. It seems, for instance, that the performing greatness
of comedian Sid Field now lives only in the memory of the second world war
generation. His films were flops. He died - from a heart attack in 1950 at
the tragically young age of 45 - before the rise of television; but by all
accounts his was an act that relied on sheer presence. Illustrious
commentators - Peter Ustinov, John Osborne, Chaplin himself - agree that
Field was the funniest clown of all. From such of his scripts as survive and
from the facts of his brief life, William Humble has put together an
agreeable portrait-show called What a Performance, directed by Roger Redfarn
and designed by Paul Farnsworth, which searches for the secret of Field's
greatness.
David Suchet takes the main role and first of all we see him in his own
person in a dressing-room set surrounded by the blackness of the bare stage,
as he puts on his wig and recites those brief facts: obscure birth in
Birmingham, childhood on the stage, quarter-century yoked by rotten
contracts to the provincial circuit, six explosive years as the biggest star
in the West End with an appearance at the Royal Variety Performance, then
burn-out and transformation into a legend, the last of the great music-hall
comedians.
Bewigged and sparkling, a cheekie chappie with a Brum accent, Suchet stays
in role from now on, as a sequence of biographical vignettes unfolds with
set-piece comic routines and songs interpolated. We see little Sid's primal
scene of instruction: a suburban tea-table at which his iron-willed
theatrical mother is holding forth while the lad pours tea in a long stream
down to a cup held on the floor by his Dad (Clive Panto), a redundant
whip-maker with a relentless sense of humour who chooses to live under the
table. Soon widowed, Marilyn Cutt's Bertha follows her son around the
country, organising his career like an implacable Mary Poppins with richly
rolled Birmingham 'r's.
It is as a mother-fixated son, a timid negotiator of contracts, a husband
turning his ear against responsibility like his ostrich-father, that we are
shown the Sid Field behind the gags. But the gags keep coming in again, and
they get Sid to heaven, at any rate, in this not very deeply pondered
exploration of his soul. Those gags were always valued for not being
'questionable' - and one does derive from the show a sense of the innocent
gutsy humour of a bygone year - but they must have been quite camp if
Suchet's performance is accurate. He is forever slipping into his pansy
voice and does not, indeed, stop short of the questionable innuendo.
But he wins the day with his skilful patter and athletic slapstick. He flies
back and forth across the stage, beautifully avoiding a strategic banana in
the palsied butler sketch (done as a lurid caricature worthy of Spitting
Image) and one is lost in admiration for the slick acting ability of his
tongue in the wide-mouthed frog routine. The interesting irony of What a
Performance, which is all about the theatre and guys the kind of West-End
first night that we were actually attending, is that even if the comedy
routines went wrong, it would only be part of the play. Given Suchet's
virtuosity and the dry brilliance of Christopher Godwin's splendidly lean,
tall, straight man, Jerry Desmonde, there is little danger of that.
Queen's Theatre, W1 (071 494 5040).
</TEXT>
<XX>
