<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / Technology (Worth Watching): Revolution on the golf course
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SHEILA JONES and LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wilson Sporting Goods of the US has launched a 'revolutionary' new golf ball
which, it says, improves performance by 'optimising interaction between
opposing aerodynamic forces of drag and lift', writes Louise Kehoe in San
Francisco.
Borrowing design principles developed in the NASA space programme, Wilson's
Ultra ball has a new dimple pattern and 100 more dimples than the average
ball, which has 400. Ultra's dimples, arranged in a 'geodesic icosahedral'
pattern of 60 spherical triangles, create a more symmetrical surface to
achieve higher velocity and more stable flight, the designers say.
The ball, which sells for about Dollars 36 per dozen, comes with different
combinations of dimples depending on whether you are going for distance, low
trajectory or high trajectory.
Wilson Sporting Goods, US: tel 312 714 6400
</TEXT>
