<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / People: Guignard quits Greycoat
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The expected board shake-out at Greycoat, the property developer rescued
from the brink of collapse almost a year ago, was announced yesterday,
perhaps rather sooner than had been thought.
However, according to Michael Beckett, who became non-executive chairman in
September: 'The sooner you do these things, the better. It is the final
stage of the group's refinancing and restructuring process, which has been
going on for a period of time. This now cements it.'
Richard Guignard, 52, and for the past three years a managing director, is
retiring from the board in an atmosphere of 'no animosity', according to
Beckett.
It was Guignard who 'was responsible for conceiving and implementing the
successful financial restructuring in 1993'. His settlement is Pounds 75,000
gross, with no extras; his salary had been Pounds 180,000.
John Weir, like Guignard with the company since 1982, has also stepped down
as an executive. He will continue to oversee the US operation 'until the
properties there are sold or transferred, probably spring next year', says
Beckett.
On the non-executive side, George Constantinidi, interim chairman until the
arrival of Beckett, and George Pitt have resigned, to be replaced by Stephen
James and David Tucker.
James recently retired as senior partner of Simmons &amp; Simmons, the City law
firm; he also has extensive property involvement. Tucker was a former deputy
managing director of M&amp;G Group and therefore 'knows the City and City
practice', according to Beckett.
Julian Treger and Brian Myerson, the South African financiers credited with
the resuscitation of the company and made non-executive directors in the
light of the 12.44 per cent shareholding of their vehicle, will remain as
non-executives. However, Treger will resign in March, when he and Myerson
will become alternate directors.
</TEXT>
