<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / People: More Bodies on Shop board
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Natural cosmetics retailer Body Shop International has appointed its first
non-executive directors, in a move to strengthen its board as the company
becomes a global retailer.
They are Penny Hughes, 35, president of Coca-Cola Great Britain and Ireland,
and Aldo Papone, 62, former chairman and chief executive of the
travel-related services arm of American Express, who is still a senior
adviser to Amex.
Body Shop said in August, when it changed the role of company founder Anita
Roddick from group managing director to chief executive, and appointed
Stuart Rose as MD - and before the recent round of criticism of the group's
'green' credentials - that it planned to take on non-executives.
It did not want these to be 'token' directors to satisfy corporate
governance guidelines, but people who could genuinely contribute to the
business.
Rose says the company has achieved that with its new appointments. Penny
Hughes, he says, has particular experience in franchise management, an
important issue for Body Shop. President of Coca-Cola GB and Ireland since
1992, she joined the company in 1984 from a marketing role with the Milk
Marketing Board.
Aldo Papone, says Rose, has a reputation in the US as a 'marketing guru'
after 20 years' involvement in developing the American Express brand image.
He began his career with Macy's department store group in 1956, and rose to
general merchandising director, before joining Amex in 1974 as president of
the travel division.
His appointment strengthens the links between Amex and Body Shop; Anita
Roddick appeared recently in TV advertising for the American Express card.
Rose says Body Shop is still looking for more non-executive directors but
will not give a number. 'We are looking for high-calibre people from diverse
backgrounds,' he says. One ideally would be an industrial entrepreneur with
international experience, another would have wide human resources
experience.
</TEXT>
