<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / Management: How to recognise the British ex-pat - Executives
who choose to live overseas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ADRIAN FURNHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
One of the many consequences of the empire is that the emigrant British
diaspora is amazingly widespread. Some countries such as the US, Australia
and South Africa may have millions of British passport holders, a good
percentage of whom regard themselves as ex-pats.
The ex-pats can be found at the country club famous for its cheap gin and
faithful retainers. But they can also be found in the local church, the
Rotarians, the Women's Institute and the British Council. Others prefer
either to blend in with the locals or keep to themselves.
But how do the British adapt to living and working abroad? Are they uniquely
effective ex-pats or is it true that, like American jokes and Bulgarian
wine, they do not travel well?
An ex-pat is usually defined as someone who makes the decision to live and
work abroad.
Many do not plan to be ex-pats but then find themselves in the role. How do
they change over time?
It seems that various ways of adapting are open to them. These different
styles may change over time and indeed they may be more common in some
countries than others. But most are immediately recognisable.
Upwardly Mobile. These ex-pats soon discover that with some technical
training, a western education, English fluency and a white skin they are top
of the pecking order.
In demographic speak a C2 is treated like an A or B socio-economic group
member. Instead of being a servant, one has servants; instead of taking
orders one gives them. Return becomes unthinkable because it means downward
mobility.
Sojourners. This group is more pragmatic with a long-term plan. They are
abroad for a specific goal and usually a set time period. It may be to
accrue capital to pay off a mortgage, or it may be to do one's duties in the
company and earn promotion on return.
They are strictly not ex-pats but are temporary sojourners on a foreign
posting, although they usually mix with the ex-pats.
Nomads. These are sequential sojourners in the sense that they pitch their
tent in one country after another, apparently aimlessly. A new pasture seems
all they are after for they follow no long-term plan. But the longer they
are abroad the harder it is to go home. They are condemned to being the
wandering albatrosses of the ex-pat world.
Financially Trapped. This group has stayed too long at a place in decline.
They do not have the option to return home because they are tied into a
pension plan and indeed a weak economy. The financially trapped may be found
in badly managed, newly independent countries where the currency has been
chronically devalued. They cannot move or go home because they have no
capital. Gone Troppo. This refers to the long-term ex-pats who have gone
native. It is, of course, much more than becoming thoroughly acquainted with
the language, the dress codes and the norms of the natives but a rejection
of one's own values.
It can sometimes look pathetic and may be induced as much by a love of
alcohol and adultery as the values and behavioural norms of the local
culture.
The Never Lefts. The most odd reaction is that of the ex-pats who behave as
if they have never left Sunningdale. They may be marooned in a tropical
paradise, but they are slavishly faithful to their old way of dress, food,
social behaviour. They maintain the style and preferences of the country
they left which now no longer exists.
In some places the ex-pats exist as if nothing has changed since the great
days of the empire. They are happy to be abroad so long as the natives are
waiters and drivers. They may have a deeply ambivalent attitude to the
mother country and the thought of coming home.
To re-pat the ex-pat is indeed a significant challenge.
Adrian Furnham is Professor of Psychology at University College London.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P874  Management and Public Relations.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
