<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / MoD extracts pledge on VSEL
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD GRAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Aerospace has had to promise the Ministry of Defence that it will
not close VSEL's Barrow shipbuilding facility in Cumbria if its takeover bid
for the yard is successful, although further redundancies at the yard seem
inevitable.
The MoD has said that BAe cannot close Barrow without its express consent as
part of the agreement to let its bid go ahead.
The Barrow yard is the last in the UK which can build big warships such as
aircraft carriers and assault ships now that the Swan Hunter yard on the
Tyne seems doomed. The MoD and the Royal Navy are insisting that BAe must
keep the yard open for national security reasons.
However, VSEL, the yard's current owner, has already planned further job
cuts at the yard as work on four Trident nuclear missile submarines winds
down in 1996-97. Work on the next batch of Trafalgar class nuclear
hunter-killer submarines is unlikely to start before 1998.
BAe is likely to continue with VSEL's redundancy plan, but because there is
relatively little overlap between BAe's and VSEL's businesses few additional
redundancies are likely to result if BAe acquires the yard. It is not clear
whether further redundancies would be involved were GEC, the other potential
bidder, to buy the yard.
Both BAe and GEC are likely to argue that bringing the Barrow yard within a
larger group is likely to strengthen its chances of winning further work in
future years and therefore offers better long-term job prospects than if
VSEL remains independent.
VSEL had been interested in acquiring Devonport dockyard, which refits
nuclear submarines, and BAe may also be interested.
Devonport is operated by a management consortium, DML, and it had thought
that VSEL might join the consortium to bid for the privatisation of the
dockyard.
There are strong overlaps between the refitting of nuclear submarines and
their original construction. BAe might replace VSEL as a potential member of
the consortium to bid for the Devonport privatisation if its attempt to
takeover VSEL is successful. Engineers and designers might then work both on
Barrow and Devonport dockyards, cutting the total number needed.
Initial bids for Devonport have to be logged with the MoD by the end of this
month, with final bids submitted next April. GEC is thought to be less
interested in Devonport, and may not join the consortium even if it does
decide to bid for VSEL. But there may be some rationalisation between the
Yarrow and Barrow yards if GEC wins control of VSEL, which could involve
further job losses.
</TEXT>
