<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / Straw calls for end to Clause 4
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Jack Straw, shadow environment secretary and a close ally of Labour
leader Mr Tony Blair, last night criticised Clause 4 of the party's
constitution as a 'sop to middle-class activists' which should be replaced
by a clear set of principles, Roland Rudd writes.
Mr Straw condemned the clause as a 'creature of its time which has long
since lost its meaning'.
He said: 'The truth is that despite Clause 4, or maybe even because of it,
Labour has throughout much of its history been a resolutely unideological
party. It is as if Clause 4 was a sop to keep middle-class party activists
happy rather than a guiding philosophy for the party.'
Mr Straw said there was little evidence that Labour in government ever
sought to take 'the means of production into public ownership' as outlined
by the clause.
Instead Labour governments pursued a more pragmatic policy and never tried
to nationalise private businesses other than public utilities, public
services and ailing companies.
It had been a convenient tool for pragmatists, he said. 'They could use it
to reassure activists that Labour was an avowedly socialist party in the
full knowledge that no one expected them to implement it. Clause 4 is a
deliberately vague and ambiguous aspiration.'
This was why the debate on Labour's aims and values was so important, he
said, since nothing short of a renewed statement of democratic socialism in
the place of Clause 4 would enthuse voters with Labour's visions of 'New
Britain'.
</TEXT>
