<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / South-east slow to escape recession
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The south-east lost one in 10 of its jobs in business and financial services
during the recession, according to a report from the region's local
authorities.
The report says that the recession has ended the traditional north-south
divide, and the south-east will not lead the country out of the downturn.
Essex, Bedford and west Sussex have the poorest growth, while
Buckinghamshire, Cambridgeshire and Berkshire are expected to grow fastest.
Women in the workforce are becoming polarised between a minority in
full-time professional and managerial jobs and a majority in low-skilled,
often part-time, manual or service occupations. A decline in clerical
employment has removed a key stepping stone between the two.
During the recession employment of those aged 16 to 25 in the south-east
dropped 29 per cent for men and 23 per cent for women, while unemployment in
this age group grew by 95 per cent for men and 28 per cent for women.
