<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / Lenders weigh up housing benefits: Private investors are
alarmed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Private investors which have furnished Pounds 5.5bn to housing associations
since 1989 to provide homes for the poor and disadvantaged have become
increasingly alarmed about their dependence on the escalating housing
benefits budget.
Ministers have identified housing benefit as a prime target as they seek to
contain public spending.
Commercial lenders say a move to cap or reduce payments would jeopardise
returns and undermine future housing investment plans.
Rent rebates and allowances are estimated to have increased to Pounds 8.65bn
in the 12 months to the end of March, a rise of 130 per cent since 1988-89.
Housing accounts for more than 10 per cent of all benefit payments compared
with 8 per cent five years ago.
Mr Douglas Smallwood, controller for policy and marketing for Halifax
building society's commercial lending division, said last week that
investors would no longer see associations as low-risk investments if their
involvement meant rents were to rise much higher.
Mr Mike Lazenby, head of housing at Nationwide building society, said:
'There is a clear political risk that ministers may intervene if rents and
benefits continue to increase sharply.'
The message from this week's Tory party conference in Bournemouth is that
payments may not be cut in the present spending round but the issue is
unlikely to go away.
At the heart of the dilemma is the increased proportion of private-finance
associations are required to raise, under the 1988 Housing Act, to pay for
new developments.
Rents have risen sharply to generate sufficient returns to attract private
investors, which from next April will be expected to provide 42 per cent of
associations' finance, compared with 25 per cent private investment in
1989-90.
According to the National Federation of Housing Associations, average weekly
housing association rents for new developments between 1988 and 1993 rose
from Pounds 29.18 to Pounds 52.45, an increase of 80 per cent.
It said that the proportion of new tenants eligible for housing benefit
since 1989-90 had increased from 67 per cent to 83 per cent. More worrying
for the government is that 49 per cent of tenants with jobs are now eligible
for benefit compared with 27 per cent five years ago.
Large numbers of tenants are caught in a poverty trap which means almost all
additional income is lost through a corresponding drop in benefit providing
little incentive for extra employment.
Commercial lenders have argued strongly that the government should not
increase the private-sector contribution to 42 per cent next April from its
present 38 per cent.
The Council for Mortgage Lenders warned in a letter to Mr David Curry,
housing minister, that further reductions in public-sector grants to housing
associations would mean 'a consequent increase in the level of exposure and
risk faced by lenders'.
Nationwide, which has lent associations almost Pounds 1bn in the past five
years, says it is likely to become more selective in its choice of
investment.
Mr Lazenby said the society would 'prefer an established association which
has been around for a number of years and has older properties which
currently generate a surplus from rental income which can be used to
cross-subsidise new rents and prevent them from rising too high'.
The outcome is that some associations, those not fitting the Nationwide
description, are likely find it more difficult to attract private investors
in future when the government is seeking to reduce the level of grants it
provides.
</TEXT>
