<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / TV food ad rules tightened
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Television advertisements will be banned from showing excessive consumption
of any food under rules being drawn up by the Independent Television
Commission, the TV watchdog.
The ITC said yesterday, however, that it had rejected calls from dentists
and food campaigners to ban fatty and sugary food advertisements from all
children's television. The ITC said it would review its policy after further
research.
The new rules on excessive consumption, designed to reinforce government
advice on healthy eating, would not stop an advertisement showing someone
enjoying a chocolate bar, said the ITC. The rules would, however, 'preclude
someone going on to open a second or a third, or pigging a whole box of
chocolates at one sitting', it said.
References to supermarket multipacks would be permitted but, the ITC said,
'filling a supermarket trolley with very large quantities of confectionery
would not'.
It is likely that an advertisement for Dime chocolate, which featured
comedian Harry Enfield loading his trolley with the bars, would fall foul of
the new rules if it were shown in future.
The ITC's proposals to revise its advertising code, which are subject to
consultation over the coming month, also outlaw 'the disparagement of good
nutritional practice'. Advertisers would be able to claim that a sweetened
fruit juice tasted delicious but not to say it was preferable to fresh fruit
or unsweetened fruit juice.
It is also likely that, under the new code, advertising slimming products to
children and adolescents will be banned.
The National Food Alliance, an umbrella group of more than 50 organisations,
said it was pleased the ITC had decided to address the issue of food
advertising but disappointed that the proposals did not go far enough. The
group said research showed children were not getting a balanced message
about nutrition from advertisements.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9651 Regulation of Miscellaneous Commercial Sectors.
    P7313 Radio, Television, Publisher Representatives.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Safety &amp; Standards.
