<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / The Loyalist Ceasefire: From jailbird to dove of peace
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Nothing perhaps better personifies the change in Northern Ireland as the
choice of Augustus 'Gusty' Spence, as yesterday's spokesman for the loyalist
paramilitaries.
The man picked to announce to the world that the para-militaries had opted
for a universal cessation of hostilities has not always been a man of peace.
Twenty-eight years ago Mr Spence formed part of a Ulster Volunteer Force
band that fired on four young Roman Catholics as they left a pub in West
Belfast, near the loyalist Shankhill Road.
One of the Catholics, 18-year-old Peter Ward, was killed. Three men,
including Mr Spence, were subsequently arrested and imprisoned for the
attack.
Many Catholics believe that murder was directly responsible for the civil
unrest and street disorder which developed later.
Mr Spence - now elderly and suffering from poor health - claims to have
undergone a Christian conversion while in prison, abandoning direct
involvement in terrorist operations. He was released from prison in 1984
after serving 16 years of a life sentence.
He has always admitted having once been a member of the UVF but denies that
he murdered Mr Ward.
He formed a youth training centre for the unemployed in the late 1980s. The
centre closed last year after getting into financial difficulties.
In a rare interview four years ago Mr Spence explained why some people in
Belfast chose to live behind walls.
He said: 'In a society of fear people stay with their own sort. We are
living in a society which has never been normal.'
In recent months he has kept in close touch with the internal debate of the
loyalist paramilitaries. Yesterday he was chosen to usher in the prospect of
at least more normal times.
</TEXT>
