<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / The Conservatives in Bournemouth: Government puts chips on
the menu for everyone - The smart-card technology which could be applied to
Tory plans to introduce identity cards - if the cost hurdle can be overcome
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The mention of identity cards is guaranteed to raise hackles in a Britain
acutely conscious of threats to civil liberties. So Shell UK's plan,
announced this month, to replace fuel tokens and trading stamps with 'smart'
cards may give government plans to introduce identity cards an unexpected
boost by making the public familiar with a technology which has so far
failed to find much favour.
Mr Michael Howard, the home secretary, was clearly referring to smart-card
technology when yesterday he talked about an identity card capable of being
a bank card, driving licence, social security card and kidney donor card.
He could, of course, have been talking about a paper document. But without
the security against fraud afforded by electronic technology it is hard to
see where the advantage in paper would lie.
Since its invention in the late 1970s the smart card - a piece of plastic
the size of a bank card with an electronic circuit embedded in it - has been
acknowledged as prime candidate for a host of applications - identity card,
security device, electronic purse and information storage.
Pioneered by the French, whose trials of the card as an electronic purse
proved the feasibility of the technology on a large scale, it has found
applications from transport systems to satellite television and public
telephones. Mastercard and Visa, the international payment groups, have said
that they intend to move to smart-card technology.
There are about 300m smart cards in circulation, and the number is expected
to increase to 3bn within the decade. Last year, according to Retail Banking
Research, about 14bn transactions were made with cards capable of being
'charged' with cash in advance.
The advantage smart cards have over conventional bank cards is the ability
to store and process large amounts of information while remaining completely
secure. The magnetic stripes on conventional cards are easy to obtain and
data can be written on the stripe using equipment not much more
sophisticated than a domestic tape recorder.
Smart cards contain memory and microprocessor chips which are hard to
counterfeit. They can store codes and carry out complex calculations which
render them tamper-proof. And they can hold, in computer language, some
physical characteristics of the card-holder - a fingerprint, for example, or
the pattern in the retina of the eye.
Together these can be used to guarantee that a card is genuine and that the
cardholder is who he or she claims to be. It can also hold extensive
information about the holder - medical history, for example, or bank
statement.
The sticking point - and one reason why banks have not already replaced
magnetic-stripe cards with electronic cheque books - is cost.
Magnetic-stripe cards cost almost nothing - about 10p each in bulk. Smart
cards are expensive.
The most common types of smart card - representing about 90 per cent of
those in issue - have little processing but extensive storage capabilities.
Mr Bernard Brooks, managing director of GPT Card Technology, which
manufactures 30m of these memory cards each year, said the cost in bulk was
about 50p.
True smart cards containing both memory and microprocessor can cost between
Pounds 5 and Pounds 20 each. They are manufactured in comparatively small
numbers by a handful of manufacturers worldwide. The terminals used to read
them vary in price from Pounds 800 for a system robust enough for street use
to Pounds 150 for a desktop box in a secure environment.
Memory cards which are adequate for use in payphones, in unscrambling
encrypted satellite video films and in storing motorists' petrol points in
Shell's scheme are not secure enough to be used as electronic wallets or
multipurpose identity cards. These applications require a true smart card
with a complete computer embedded in it.
Mondex, an electronic purse which National Westminster Bank, Midland Bank
and British Telecommunications intend to test next year, uses Japanese-made
computer chips.
Some manufacturers are looking for ways to cut the cost by combining
magnetic technology with microelectronics. Thorn EMI has developed a smart
card which does away with expensive data encryption on the chip in favour of
a development of its 'watermark' technology which makes cards hard to tamper
with.
Dr David Arnold of Thorn's Transaction Group said the cost of the chip could
be cut significantly by minimising its size.
Advanced Risc Machines, the UK-based microprocessor company owned by Acorn,
Apple of the US and VLSI, is talking to Gemplus of France, Europe's biggest
smart-card manufacturer, with a view to using low-cost, low-power processors
in smart cards.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
