<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / The Conservatives in Bournemouth: Monks urges less hostility
to unions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Monks, the TUC general secretary, told the government last night
that ending hostility towards unions could help the party retain power at
the next election.
He warned ministers that attacks on unions were no longer an automatic way
of winning votes.
He added: 'Even if that were ever the case, it certainly is not true any
more. People now look to trade unions to support them in a world of work
that is uncertain and insecure.'
Mr Monks, the first TUC chief to speak at a fringe meeting at the
Conservative party conference, said more and more workers afraid of losing
their jobs were looking to the unions for support.
However, he said, a visit by a union leader to a political party conference
would pass with little comment in any other European country. 'Only in
Britain is there such deep distrust and mutual suspicion between trade
unions and government.'
To take over Labour's lead in the opinion polls the Conservatives would
require the votes of 'many more trade unionists'.
Mr Monks said it could not be 'good politics' for the Conservatives to
continue to be seen as anti-union when an opinion poll had recorded 89 per
cent support for the view that unions were necessary to protect people's
interests at work.
The problem faced by the government was that most people recognised that the
relationship between employer and employee was 'fundamentally one-sided'.
Mr Monks said: 'The world of work is autocratic and dominated by top-down
management power, and getting more so.'
He attacked the government for excluding Britain from the social chapter of
the Maastricht treaty.
Mr Monks argued that people reluctant to accept that an economic recovery
was under way were hardly likely to believe that having fewer rights at work
than were available in other countries was a crucial ingredient for success.
</TEXT>
