<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / The Conservatives in Bournemouth: Portillo stresses fight
against 'pernicious' inflation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Portillo yesterday underlined the government's commitment to low
inflation, arguing that stable prices helped mobilise investment and
preserve the welfare state.
The employment secretary said in a speech to the Conservative Political
Centre group that maintaining low inflation assisted the government to
mobilise private capital for infrastructure investment.
He said that with high and unpredictable rates of inflation in much of the
period since the second world war the provision of infrastructure had become
a state monopoly.
Low inflation was also essential to the government's aim of a 'modern and
affordable welfare state'. Only with low inflation would people be
encouraged to provide for their own retirement. In times of high inflation
'inevitably people look to the state to do more and provide larger pensions
to compensate for the decline in value of their own schemes and their
savings', he said.
Although Mr Portillo's speech was low key compared with some of his other
interventions at this year's conference, it nonetheless marked out his claim
 -as a former Treasury minister - to have a say in determining government
economic policy.
Mr Portillo said inflation affected the government's management of the
nation's finances. He noted that in the last Budget Mr Kenneth Clarke, the
chancellor, raised taxes by far less than the amount by which he reduced
borrowing because low inflation enabled the government to keep a tight grip
on its spending.
Mr Portillo predicted that in future 'balanced budgets will be the order of
the day, just as they were for governments in the 19th century'.
Inflation, Mr Portillo said, was 'a pernicious form of hidden tax' that
'amounts to dishonest government'. Inflation in Britain had exerted a bad
effect on industrial relations, savings, investment, resource allocation and
on management. It had reduced efficiency and productivity and thus held back
the growth of living standards.
Expectations of inflation were the 'ugly sister' of inflation. In
anticipation of inflation businesses pushed prices higher. Capital was
diverted away from investment in productive projects into less risky assets
such as gilt-edged stock. As a legacy of high inflation investors continued
to demand high nominal returns even when inflation was low.
Mr Portillo said the economies that Britain sought to emulate - notably
Japan and Germany - did not tolerate inflation. He recalled that during the
past 20 years there had been only two years when UK inflation was lower than
Germany's. These were 1992 and 1993. 'We are determined this will not be a
brief flash in the pan,' he said. The permanent defeat of inflation was 'at
the top' of the government's political agenda.
</TEXT>
