<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / The Conservatives in Bournemouth: Bookies predict
nine-minute ovation
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The prime minister is likely to get a nine minute standing ovation when he
addresses the conference today, according to odds issued by William Hill,
the bookmakers.
The company offered relatively short odds of 3-1 against a nine minute
ovation, compared to 4-1 for seven minutes or less, 7-2 for eight minutes,
4-1 for 10 minutes, 8-1 for 11 minutes and 7-2 for 12 minutes or more. Bets
will be settled on the time for the ovation calculated by the Press
Association news agency.
Mr Major received conference ovations lasting 9 1/2 minutes in 1991, about
seven minutes in 1992, when applause merged into singing, and 11 minutes in
1993.
His predecessor Lady Thatcher often received ovations lasting eight to 10
minutes. Her longest was more than 11 minutes in 1987.
