<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / World Trade News: Uruguay Round to face delay in Japan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Last minute wrangling by Japan's ruling party politicians with backing from
the powerful rice lobby is threatening to disrupt ratification of a
legislative package to implement the Uruguay Round trade treaty.
Japan has agreed partially to open its rice market from next year, and next
week the cabinet is scheduled to approve Uruguay Round legislation,
including a law on rice production and distribution, before submitting it to
parliament.
However, politicians from farming communities are upset about the absence of
farm subsidy guarantees within a supplementary farm measures package aimed
at supporting farmers affected by implementation of both the international
trade agreements and the Uruguay Round accords.
Some are threatening to boycott approval of the legislation unless a
substantial amount of aid for farmers is included in the support package.
Some politicians have been reported as demanding support amounting to up to
Y6,000bn (Dollars 60bn) over the next six years.
The Ministry of Finance is opposed to any such farm subsidy guarantees and
negotiations with the Agriculture ministry, which is being prodded by the
farm lobby, are deadlocked. The government is expected to announce the
measures next week, and agricultural committees of coalition parties are
pushing Mr Tomiichi Murayama, the prime minister, for a political
settlement.
The rice lobby wants Japan to delay Uruguay Round ratification until its
trading partners pass their implementing legislation. Mr Murayama yesterday
endorsed this view in a parliamentary comment that ratification procedures
in the US and EU nations needed to be observed carefully. This means Japan's
ratification of the Uruguay Round legislation package is now unlikely until
the US congress convenes at the end of November to vote on the trade
measures.
</TEXT>
