<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / US producer prices down 0.5% in month: Fall in energy costs
holds index back
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US producers' prices fell by 0.5 per cent last month, as a sharp drop in
energy prices offset more expensive metals and intermediate goods.
The Department of Labor said the core producer price index, excluding
volatile food and energy prices, rose by just 0.1 per cent in September,
much less than most private sector economists had predicted, leaving a
year-on-year inflation rate of 1.9 per cent.
Prices for crude materials, meanwhile, fell 1.6 per cent, while intermediate
goods prices rose 0.3 per cent, much less than in recent months.
That helped to soothe the financial markets' fears of a surge in inflation,
as many economists watch producer prices as an earlier indicator of
inflationary pressures.
But the core indices for crude and intermediate goods, again excluding food
and energy, rose more sharply in September. Core prices for crude materials
rose by 1.3 per cent in September and have climbed 13.7 per cent in the last
12 months, while prices for core intermediate materials rose by 0.6 per cent
in September and by 3.5 per cent over the last year.
However, Federal Reserve economists tend to regard both the producer price
index and the consumer price index, which is due to be published today, as
more backward-looking measurements than advance warnings of inflationary
pressures.
Although analysts had generally predicted a sharp drop for energy prices,
which fell by 2.9 per cent in September, they miscalculated badly on car
prices.
These fell by 1.1 per cent in September, whereas most analysts, expecting
smaller than usual discounts as dealers sold off vehicles from the last
model year, had expected another increase on top of August's 0.7 per cent.
Tobacco prices, on the other hand, rose by 2.0 per cent after a 1.4 per cent
increase in August and price increases also accelerated for prescription and
over-the-counter drugs, books, mobile homes and household furniture.
Economists disagreed on the implications of the Labour Department's price
data.
Mr Bruce Steinberg of Merrill Lynch described the producer price index as
'terrific'.
'It doesn't mean that there is no inflation pressure. Does it mean that
people have exaggerated the extent of inflationary pressure? I think so,' he
said.
But Mr Joseph Liro of SG Warburg warned: 'As reassuring as the headline
number were, dark clouds remain on the horizon.' He pointed to the rises in
core crude and intermediate goods prices as signs of increasing pressure on
producers to raise their prices.
</TEXT>
