<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / Nasa to auction space machinery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
For sale by private treaty or negotiation: a few boring machines, never
used, one careful owner, apply to auctioneers in London or the US.
The machines, however, are only boring in the engineering sense and the sale
is far from ordinary: more than Dollars 120m (Pounds 76m) of equipment is up
for grabs in a worldwide sale on behalf of the National Aeronautics and
Space Administration (Nasa). This is the largest sale of space technology
manufacturing plant to come on the open market.
The equipment comes from a Dollars 2bn project to develop an advanced solid
rocket motor for the Space Shuttle. Rocket casings made at Mount Vernon,
Indiana, were to be floated down the Mississippi to a propellant plant at
Iuka, Mississippi, loaded and then floated into the Gulf of Mexico and round
to Cape Canaveral.
Last October, however, with mounting budget pressures and continued safe
performance of the existing shuttle motor, Congress killed the project. The
only problem was that the factories had been built and equipped.
Nasa has given the task of selling the production equipment to National
Industrial Services of the US, which has enlisted Henry Butcher, the London
plant and machinery consultants, to handle the sale outside North America.
The two organisations have to find buyers for some of the world's biggest,
and most sophisticated machine tools - most of them specially built in 1991
to Nasa's exacting standards, and mostly never used. Apart from boring
machines, there are sophisticated machining centres and welding stations,
and everything from overhead cranes to process mixers and electrical
substations.
'This has to be the finest sale of so-called second-hand machine tools and
process plant that has ever come on to the open market,' Mr John Cowing of
Henry Butcher said yesterday. He expected worldwide interest in the sale.
The 100 main items for sale have price tags ranging from Dollars 3m to a
mere Dollars 30,000. It is understood the total raised will be considerably
less than the original investment, which included research and development
spending.
Peripheral building services equipment will be sold in an auction at Iuka on
November 2 and 3, but the main items will go by private treaty or negotiated
sale.
</TEXT>
