<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / Cardoso's congress challenge: The politics awaiting Brazil's
new president
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Brazil's next president, Mr Fernando Henrique Cardoso, delighted cartoonists
by going fishing after he was elected on October 3. It provided an
irresistible cartoon theme, since he will be spending the coming months
angling for support in Congress.
Mr Cardoso, who takes office on January 1, needs to build a majority in a
Congress which is still maturing after Brazil's return to democracy 10 years
ago. He needs three-fifths support, a more daunting prospect, to make a
number of urgent constitutional reforms. Without strong backing to make
these changes, his presidency could be undermined by factional disputes and
become a weak coalition government, as happened with two of his three
predecessors.
Mr Cardoso has a number of advantages. What is most important, he was
elected with more than 54 per cent of the valid votes. So he does not face
the credibility problems of the current president, Mr Itamar Franco, and
former president, Mr Jose Sarney, who were both promoted from vice-president
rather than being directly elected.
He also has the basis for a working majority in Congress. An election
alliance between his Social Democracy party (PSDB), the right-wing Liberal
Front (PFL) and another smaller party appears to be holding firm. These
parties have 209 senators and deputies and should be able to attract enough
extra votes to guarantee a congressional majority of 298 votes on many
subjects.
The PSDB's strong showing in the elections will also lift Mr Cardoso's power
inside his coalition. The number of PSDB deputies in the lower house is
likely to have increased by half to more than 60, giving it a similar
strength to the historically much larger PFL.
Despite these advantages, Mr Cardoso faces a number of problems. In the
short term, elections for governor for some of the country's most important
states were undecided last week and run-offs will be held next month. Allies
of Mr Cardoso appear likely to win in three key states, Sao Paulo, Rio
Grande do Sul and Bahia. Mr Cardoso needs state governors to support his
planned constitutional reforms in areas such as tax collection and state
spending cuts. If his allies do win in the second round, Mr Cardoso will
have the support of about half of the 27 state governors.
The main obstacle to building congressional alliances is that most
politicians are loyal to individual leaders or local interests rather than
parties or national issues. For example, the PFL is controlled by Mr Antonio
Carlos Magalhaes whose support helped elect 22 deputies for his home state
of Bahia. Mr Magalhaes is backing Mr Cardoso for the moment. But he or other
conservative PFL leaders may not support some of Mr Cardoso's more
adventurous social policies, for example on resettling landless farmers.
A further complicating factor is that about half the new Congress members
were elected for the first time, making it difficult to predict how they
will act. 'It's going to take (Mr Cardoso) time to build a majority and it
won't be unconditional; it will be on a case-by-case basis,' says Mr
Alexandre Barros, a political consultant.
On some subjects, Mr Cardoso will look for support from the Democratic
Movement party (PMDB), the country's largest. Its candidate, Mr Orestes
Quercia, polled less than 5 per cent of votes in the presidential election
and is likely to want the party to oppose Mr Cardoso.
But, says Mr Luiz Pedone, a political scientist, there are four different
factions in the PMDB, and Mr Quercia's appears on the decline. Mr Sarney,
now a PMDB senator, may back Mr Cardoso and take several PMDB deputies with
him. The party's supporters in Rio Grande do Sul also favour supporting Mr
Cardoso rather than Mr Quercia, and may even risk splitting the party.
Even if Mr Cardoso wins over a majority of the PMDB, he may not have the
three-fifths support of Congress needed for constitutional changes. Most
analysts agree the tax and social security systems need to be completed
quickly so as to protect the government's budget.
Some proposals, for example increasing the central government's tax take or
lifting the retirement age, can only be approved via constitutional
amendments and are likely to be unpopular.
The left-wing Workers' party (PT), which will form the nucleus of
opposition, did well in the congressional elections on October 3, increasing
its number of senators from one to five and that of its deputies from 36 to
50. With other left-wing parties, the PT has about half the 156 votes needed
to block any constitutional amendments.
Mr Cardoso is therefore likely to be forced to make a series of shifting
alliances to win support from the right to pass reforms in areas such as tax
reform, and from the left on social issues. Juggling these interests will be
difficult, although Mr Cardoso has proved a skilled negotiator.
The danger is that with the private sector urging him to act quickly to
capitalise on enthusiasm about his election, it will take time to negotiate
these alliances and proposals will be watered down. There is little chance
of constitutional changes being proposed to Congress this year, and
negotiations may not begin until after the Carnival festival next February.
Mr Francisco Weffort, a political scientist at the University of Sao Paulo,
says Mr Cardoso will be able to carry off the juggling act if he guarantees
to opponents and allies that certain sensitive parts of the constitution
will not be changed. As an example, he suggests Mr Cardoso may push for the
lifting of the state's oil monopoly and allow foreign competition by
agreeing not to privatise Petrobras, the state-owned oil company, which many
politicians still see as a strategic national asset.
'He will need to reach some sort of understanding on what can and cannot be
touched for constitutional changes to go ahead,' Mr Weffort says.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>BRZ  Brazil, South America.
</CN>
<XX>
