<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / Haitian military's assets protected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TED BARDACKE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The US government will unfreeze the assets of the leaders and supporters of
Haiti's military coup now that many of them are going into exile in Panama
and the US.
Washington also announced that as part of the arrangement to get coup leader
Lt Gen Raoul Cedras to leave Haiti, it would rent his home and beach villa
for at least a year with payment made in advance. US officials denied they
were pampering coup leaders and their families.
'Our intent was to make Cedras' departure as smooth as possible and to hold
down the level of violence,' Mr Stanley Schrager, US embassy spokesman, said
in explaining why the US paid for two charter aircraft, one to take Gen
Cedras and his immediate family to Panama on Wednesday and another to take
23 other relatives and associates to Miami, in addition to leasing his
property in Haiti.
The US military will thus be protecting Gen Cedras' property, preventing the
kind of looting and destruction that happened at the home of former police
chief Michel Francois when he fled to the Dominican Republic last week. Four
US amoured vehicles were stationed outside Gen Cedras' home keeping away a
jubilant crowd that danced and sang songs in support of exiled president
Jean-Bertrand Aristide, who is to return to Haiti tomorrow.
The assets of the coup leaders, which one US official said were 'tens of
millions of dollars', were frozen in mid-1993 as the US increased pressure
on the military to leave power.
Some of the funds were raised through smuggling operations controlled by the
military which circumvented the international economic embargo imposed on
the country. Other assets, according to testimony given to the US Senate in
early 1994, were acquired through drug smuggling operations overseen by the
Haitian military.
President Aristide had been given access to some of the money during his
three years in exile, using it to bankroll extensive lobbying efforts in
Washington.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>HTZ  Haiti, Caribbean.
</CN>
