<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / US cool to Iraqi-Russian overture on Kuwaiti border
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK NICHOLSON, STEWART DALBY and GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BAGHDAD, JEDDAH, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Iraq last night announced its 'willingness' to recognise the sovereignty of
Kuwait and its UN-demarcated border, but the US responded coolly, foreseeing
no early easing of sanctions against the Baghdad regime.
The move came in a joint Iraqi-Russian statement after talks between
President Saddam Hussein, the Iraqi leader, and Mr Andrei Kozyrev, Russia's
foreign minister, who arrived in Baghdad yesterday.
The statement amounts to Iraq's most explicit step towards formal
recognition of Kuwait and its borders - a condition the UN Security Council
demands before lifting any sanctions such as the ban on Iraqi oil exports.
But it fell short of unequivocal recognition, declaring: 'Iraq confirmed its
willingness to solve the issue of recognising Kuwait and its borders as
demanded by Security Council resolution 833 in a positive manner.'
The statement appeared to peg recognition to UN Security Council agreement
to start a six-month test period of Iraq's weapons monitoring programme. Its
ambiguous phrasing suggested Iraq was insisting the UN fix a definite
timetable for the testing, leading naturally to lifting of sanctions.
It stated: 'Following Iraq's formal recognition of Kuwait's sovreignty and
borders, Russia will support the specifying of the start of the formal
operation of the long-term monitoring system in accordance with Security
Council resolution 715.' It said that the monitoring period 'should not
exceed six months', and that 'from the Russian point of view' the Security
Council should then lift sanctions if Iraq had complied during that period.
Although Russia, France and China favoured giving Iraq such a clear
timetable before last week's Iraqi troop movements, Britain and the US have
opposed such a move.
In Washington, a US official said last night an Iraqi agreement to recognise
Kuwait would not lead to an early lifting of UN sanctions. Recognising
Kuwait was 'only one element in the list of things Iraq has to do', the
official said, adding: 'We would not see any possibility of easing sanctions
at this point.'
Nevertheless, Iraq will hope that the Russian initiative, which followed
talks earlier this week between Mr Saddam and two senior Russian envoys,
will re-open debate in the Security Council over linking the lifting of
sanctions to the start of the weapons monitoring programme - debate which
was effectively closed by Iraq's latest troop movements near the Kuwait
border.
Meanwhile, two Iraqi Republican Guard brigades were reported last night to
have halted their withdrawal from the Kuwaiti border area. They were
reported to have dug in around the southern city of Nasiriyah, 100km
north-west of Basra and well within easy striking distance of the Kuwait
border.
A US official said the Iraqi units might believe they had moved far enough
to satisfy US and allied demands. But the Pentagon said the Iraqis were
still close enough to strike quickly into Kuwait.
Earlier, Mr William Perry, US defence secretary, said the US troop build-up
in the Gulf would reach only 30,000 and troops could start going home within
weeks after Iraq withdraws forces from the Kuwait border. A more powerful
force of US warplanes would remain for the foreseeable future.
US and French officials clashed yesterday over US proposals for a military
exclusion zone in southern Iraq. Ms Madeleine Albright, US ambassador to the
UN, called Mr Francois Leotard, French defence minister, 'ill-informed and
counter productive' for saying the build-up of US troops in Kuwait was 'not
unconnected' to US domestic politics. She said Mr Leotard's remarks 'give
comfort to a brutal dictator' and suggested France's position was motivated
by its commercial links with Iraq.
The row spoilt efforts by Mr Douglas Hurd, the British foreign secretary, to
paper over differences among western allies on establishing an exclusion
zone in southern Iraq.
The US has stepped back from earlier suggestions for barring tanks and heavy
military equipment from a vast demilitarised zone stretching up to the 32nd
parallel - the boundary of the existing no-fly zone. But US officials insist
some way must be found to avoid having to make costly troop deployment any
time Mr Saddam wants to play cat-and-mouse games.
Mr Hurd, speaking at a press conference in Bahrain before flying to Saudi
Arabia, said an exclusion zone was an option which came under the category
of 'some way' to be found to stop a recurrence of the Iraqi troop build-up.
Another option, a pre-emptive airstrike, appears to have receded.
One problem with a ground exclusion zone, which mirrors the air exclusion
zone, is that it could be seen as a step towards dismemberment of Iraq.
Although no western country wants Mr Saddam to remain in power, they remain
committed to the territorial integrity of Iraq, if only as a buffer against
Iran.
</TEXT>
