<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / US and France clash over exclusion zone in southern Iraq
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM, STEWART DALBY and MARK NICHOLSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, JEDDAH, BAGHDAD
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US and French officials clashed sharply yesterday over American proposals
for establishing a military exclusion zone in southern Iraq.
Ms Madeleine Albright, the US ambassador to the UN, called Mr Francois
Leotard, the French defence minister, 'very ill-informed and counter
productive' for saying the build-up of US troops in Kuwait to counter an
apparent threat from Iraq was 'not unconnected to domestic politics'.
Ms Albright said Mr Leotard's remarks 'give comfort to a brutal dictator who
is a repeat offender,' and suggested that France's own position was
motivated by its commercial links with Iraq.
The row spoilt efforts by Mr Douglas Hurd, the British foreign secretary, to
paper over differences among western allies on establishing an exclusion
zone in southern Iraq.
The US has stepped back from earlier suggestions for barring tanks and heavy
military equipment from a vast demilitarised zone stretching up to the 32nd
parallel - the boundary of the existing no-fly zone.
Nevertheless, US officials insist some way must be found to avoid having to
make a costly troop deployment any time Iraqi President Saddam Hussein wants
to play mouse and cat games.
'For the future, obviously, we do not want to have to face Saddam Hussein's
threats every few years in intimidating his neighbours and intimidating the
UN, so we are in the process of trying to negotiate a resolution in the UN
that would give us more permanent protection for the future,' Mr Leon
Panetta, the White House chief of staff, said yesterday.
Mr William Perry, the US defence secretary, said the US troop build-up would
reach only 30,000 and the troops could start returning home within weeks
after Iraq withdraws forces from the Kuwait border.
A more powerful force of US warplanes would remain for the foreseeable
future to police Baghdad's actions and make sure Mr Saddam does not again
threaten moderate Gulf states.
The bulk of US combat troops will leave quickly when Iraqi forces complete
their current retreat from southern Iraq, Mr Perry told reporters travelling
with him from Washington to visit with American forces and hold talks with
government leaders in Saudi Arabia and Kuwait.
The peak of American troops expected to reach the Gulf would thus fall far
short of the nearly 200,000 combat troops that Washington was prepared to
send unless Iraq backed down.
Mr Hurd, speaking at a press conference in Bahrain before flying to Saudi
Arabia, said an exclusion zone was an option which comes under the category
of 'some way' to be found to stop a recurrence of the Iraqi troops build-up.
Another option, a pre-emptive airstrike, appears to have receded.
One problem with a ground exclusion zone, which mirrors the air exclusion
zone is that it could be seen as a step towards the dismemberment of Iraq.
Although no western country wants Mr Saddam to remain in power, they remain
committed to the territorial integrity of Iraq, if only as a buffer against
Iran.
The Gulf states generally, and Saudi Arabia in particular, are highly
nervous about what officials call Iran's subversive inclinations. Saudi
Arabia regards Iran as a threat because it encourages Islamic extremists
within the kingdom in their anti-western stance.
Officials say that if the imposition of an extensive ground exclusion zone
now looks unlikely, more limited territorial restrictions could be imposed.
There could be a military free-zone organised around Basra, a tank-free zone
that would allow ground troops to remain in southern Iraq, or more intensive
monitoring of Iraqi troop movements.
Russia yesterday intensified its attempts to create a durable diplomatic
resolution with the arrival in Baghdad of Mr Andrei Kozyrev, the Russian
foreign minister, on a shuttle that would also include several Gulf states.
Diplomats in Baghdad said Mr Kozyrev is likely to seek a formula which might
revive the prospect of giving Iraq a set of definitive criteria for an
eventual lifting of sanctions, on condition that Iraq commits itself to the
unequivocal recognition of its border with Kuwait.
Moscow might also be eyeing an eventual revival of Iraq as a purchaser of
conventional weaponry, which would be permitted once sanctions are lifted.
Mr Hurd said sanctions against Iraq must remain.
'Iraq has not recognised Kuwait. I do not know of any country which favours
lifting sanctions while this situation continues,' Mr Hurd said.
US military officials say no limit has been set on how long US troops will
stay in Kuwait, and this could depend on the success of US negotiations in
the UN.
</TEXT>
