<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / War of nerves carries a crippling price tag: Two generations
of Kuwaitis have been cocooned from income tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBIN ALLEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Kuwait is once again bracing itself to pay a large part of the costs for the
US - and British - military presence in Kuwait and the northern Gulf as a
result of the latest confrontation with Iraq.
But in spite of paying out, by its own estimates, Dollars 47bn - half its
total reserves - to finance the cost of coalition forces liberating Kuwait
in 1991, the government has barely started to educate the public, let alone
convince the national assembly (parliament) that the days of a tax-free
existence are over.
On Wednesday Mr Warren Christopher, US secretary of state, said the US,
Britain and the six states of the Gulf Co-operation Council (Bahrain,
Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and the UAE) had agreed 'to share the cost
of the joint effort and to set up a fund', which would assess the costs and
agree the amounts to be paid by each.
In practice, however, Kuwait is uneasily aware it and Saudi Arabia will be
expected to come up with the lion's share, which will increase the longer US
forces are stationed in Kuwait for its protection.
Already, Kuwaiti newspapers are reflecting public concern about the extent
and the permanence of Iraq's withdrawal. 'How soon, how far, how long?' ran
the headline in Wednesday's Arab Times. Kuwaitis have concluded that this
chapter in the war of nerves will continue for some time.
If the last Gulf crisis cost Kuwait Dollars 47bn and Saudi Arabia some
Dollars 60bn, this time around the figures may be in the low billions of
dollars.
'Whatever has to be done will be done,' Mr Ali Rashaid al-Bader, managing
director of the Kuwait Investment Authority (KIA), said.
The KIA manages Kuwait's reserves both in the State General Reserve, which
holds all of the unrealisable assets such as historic and irredeemable loans
to third-world countries, allocations to international institutions such as
the IMF, and assets of Kuwait Airways; and the Reserve Fund for Future
Generations (RFFG), which contains the quality and liquid assets.
A recent report by the planning ministry put the total value of Kuwait's
reserves for the fiscal year ending June 30 1994 at KD18.5bn (Dollars 61bn).
Of this Dollars 23.1bn was in the general reserve, and the larger amount,
Dollars 37.9bn, in the RFFG. According to Al-Shall Economic Consultants,
KIA's investment income and asset appreciation last year added Dollars 6bn
to the value of reserves.
However, actual budget deficits for the last three years have amounted to
KD1.57bn (Dollars 5.2bn) in 1992/93, KD1.2bn (Dollars 4bn) in 1993/94, and
is projected at KD1.85bn (Dollars 6.1bn) for this fiscal year. Economists
have pointed out that oil revenues, which make up 88 per cent of the total,
are conservatively predicated at Dollars 12 a barrel; and further that
annual defence costs of KD500m (Dollars 1.65bn) are for the first time
included in estimated expenditures. Set against this is the likelihood this
year of lower returns from KIA investments and the fact that budget defence
figures represent only current expenditure, not capital costs for arms
purchases.
The defence reinforcement budget amounts to Dollars 11.5bn, to be spread
over 12 years from 1992, at the rate of up to roughly Dollars 1bn a year.
But the government has already spent or committed Dollars 4bn in two years.
Defence expenditure now accounts for 70 per cent of total average oil
revenue of the last two fiscal years. Commitments from this most recent
crisis will mean still more outflows.
The national assembly has consistently refused to countenance any suggestion
of income taxes on Kuwaiti residents or any corporate tax on Kuwaiti
companies. For two generations Kuwaitis have been cocooned. This latest
crisis is beginning to concentrate their minds.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>KWZ  Kuwait, Middle East.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9721 International Affairs.
</IN>
