<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / Growth creates Australian jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMILIA TAGAZA
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MELBOURNE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Further signs of economic recovery in Australia emerged yesterday with the
announcement of a continuing growth in the number of jobs created during the
last three months. Figures published by the official statistics bureau
showed the seasonally adjusted unemployment rate remained at 9.5 per cent in
September, despite the substantial rise in the number of people who actively
looked for jobs during the month.
Nearly 76,000 jobs were created in September, while the 'participation
rate', the percentage of working age population actively seeking work, rose
to 63.3 per cent from 62.8 per cent in August. Mr Simon Crean, the
employment minister, said this reflected the confidence of the labour force
in a growing economy. The Labor government's promise of creating 500,000
jobs in five years (from 1993) will be easily achieved. During the last
three months, 140,000 jobs have been created and analysts are predicting
that the 3 per cent growth in employment forecast in the government's
1994/95 budget will be exceeded. New capital expenditure during the three
months to June increased 7.7 per cent in constant prices, the best figure
since the September quarter of 1990. Spending on plant equipment during the
period rose 14 per cent in real terms.
</TEXT>
