<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / Radical reform of UN peacekeeping urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD MORTIMER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Radical reform of the United Nations system of crisis prevention,
peacekeeping and humanitarian relief is called for in a hard-hitting
post-mortem on the Rwanda emergency, published yesterday by the British
charity Oxfam.
The report places primary responsibility for the genocide, this summer, when
up to 1m died, on extremist Rwandan politicians. But the international
community and its most powerful member states have through 'complacency and
inaction, contributed to the slaughter'. The catalogue of failure,it says,
included:
Failure to put sufficient pressure on the Rwandan government to comply with
a UN special rapporteur's recommendations in August 1993, notably
dismantling party militias.
Pressure on the UN secretary-general to save money by cutting the UN force
in Rwanda between October 1993 and March 1994.
Arms supplies, notably by France and the US, to the previous Rwandan
government, despite evidence of gross human rights violations.
Cutting the UN force by 75% after 10 Belgian soldiers were killed in April
1994.
Deliberate delay by major powers in the Security Council in setting up a new
peacekeeping force. The US, according to Oxfam, 'took the lead in this
shameful abdication of responsibility', refusing to acknowledge genocide was
taking place and lobbying to confine the new force to border areas, despite
'clear evidence the majority under threat were within Rwanda'.
Failure by the most powerful UN members to offer troops and failure to
provide sufficient equipment and logistical support for troops offered by
African states. As a result the second UN force did not arrive until months
after killings began and 'genocide proceeded unabated and unopposed'.
Oxfam admits it is unrealistic to suggest a UN force of 5,500 could have
brought killings to an immediate halt. But 'the lame excuses of governments.
. . have been given the lie by the successful protection of thousands of
civilians by the rump UN force that remained in Kigali, by the ability of
the French troops to restore security in the south-west, and by the speed
with which Security Council members deployed troops when they chose to act,
in response to the refugee crisis in Goma'.
Rwanda: An Agenda for International Action, by Guy Vassall-Adams. Oxfam
Publications, Pounds 3.95 + 80p postage.
</TEXT>
