<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / Ukraine avoids currency panic
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MATTHEW KAMINSKI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KIEV
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Ukraine's volatile currency, the karbovanets, has fallen sharply in recent
days, losing 6 per cent of its value against the dollar yesterday and 12 per
cent since Monday, raising fears of higher inflation this winter. The
karbovanets, also called the coupon, sold at 100,000 to the dollar on the
open market yesterday, a 50 per cent fall since September 12.
The currency's latest fall follows Ukraine's decision last Friday to abolish
the government's artificial exchange rate and reopen free currency auctions.
The move was the first step in a comprehensive economic reform programme
announced by President Leonid Kuchma earlier this week, but, thanks to
inflationary credits inherited from the previous administration, the initial
impact of reform has been further destabilisation. Unlike the panic caused
by the Russian rouble's sharp fluctuations, Ukrainians this week remained
nonplussed about the latest devaluations. Public confidence in the
karbovanets has never recovered from last year's hyper-inflation - when the
annual inflation rate exceeded 10,000 per cent - and, although many
purchases are made in karbovantsi, few Ukrainians hold their savings in the
national currency.
This autumn's devaluation stems largely from a massive credit release to
agriculture this summer. The credits, authorised by parliament, derailed the
Ukrainian central bank's tight monetary policy, which brought the inflation
rate down to single digits during the first half of the year. As a result,
commercial banks are releasing around Kbv5,000bn (Dollars 53.2m) onto the
currency exchange market each week, according Mr Mykola Melnychuk, a
Ukrainian national bank official.
</TEXT>
