<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / Rural Finland holds out against EU: Finnish farmers have a
worse deal with Brussels than the Germans and Danes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Vesa Rantala farms 40 boggy hectares carved out of the Finnish forest by
his great-grandfather. Like the vast majority of Finland's agricultural
community, he is going to vote No in Sunday's referendum on joining the
European Union. He expresses his opposition with a farmer's characteristic
bluntness.
'The deal with Brussels on Finnish farming is crazy,' Mr Rantala declares,
raising his voice to be heard above the noisy lowing of his small herd of
dairy cows, already brought inside the cattle shed for the long Nordic
winter.
Although opinion polls signal the outcome on Sunday will be a yes to EU
membership, the determined opposition of Mr Rantala and his fellow farmers
has formed the core of a no campaign which has unsettled the pro-EU
political establishment in Helsinki.
Farmers make up only 7 per cent of Finland's 2m workforce and agriculture
accounts for less than 3 per cent of economic output. But their influence
extends far beyond the limits suggested by such figures in a country where
more than 35 per cent of the 5m population still live in rural areas and
many more believe it is important to avoid rural depopulation, in part to
protect the nation's security on its long border with Russia.
The farm community is the bedrock of support for the Centre party, which
under the leadership of Mr Esko Aho, the present prime minister, became the
country's biggest political party in the last general election and leads the
ruling coalition government. The party is split over the issue and several
senior party figures are campaigning for a no vote.
The angry opposition to the EU by the farmers, orchestrated by their union,
the MTK, is therefore the most serious obstacle facing the government, and
the main opposition Social Democratic party, in their efforts to win
Sunday's referendum.
What makes the farming issue awkward is a feeling among many Finns - even
those who do not believe the EU vote should be decided on agriculture - that
the EU farm deal is unfair on Finland.
Under the terms for Finland's accession to the EU, the Union rejected
Helsinki's demand that the whole country be treated as a special
agricultural case because of its severe Arctic and sub-Arctic climate.
Instead, a complex map was drawn up dividing the country into areas which
qualified for differing grades of agricultural and regional subsidies and
support. The majority of the country qualifies at least as a so-called Less
Favoured Area, or LFA, eligible for subsidies on a per-hectare basis on top
of normal EU price support.
But 15 per cent of Finland - the most southerly regions where most of the
country's cereal and vegetable production is based - does not qualify. Mr
Rantala's farm, in the district of Elimaki about 110km north-east of
Helsinki, falls some 15km outside the LFA limit. This means that he does not
qualify for any extra subsidies, despite the fact that thousands of farms in
more productive regions of the EU well to the south of southern Finland do
fall within LFAs.
The MTK says its studies show that farms in LFA-designated regions of
Germany may receive up to three-times the EU subsidy available to farmers
like Mr Rantala, despite having land with average cereal yields  - at almost
7 tonnes per hectare - twice as high as in Finland.
This is because their higher yields trigger higher payments under the Common
Agricultural Policy reform programme and they receive LFA payments.
'This is the problem,' says Mr Rantala, a Centre party local councillor
whose 40 hectares is divided between pasture, hay and cereals. 'When they
are sowing spring seed, our land is still snowbound. We cannot sow until
May. The quality of our soil and climate is so different. It is ridiculous
that I am put on a worse basis than farmers in Germany and Denmark.'
The other furious complaint by the MTK is over the EU insistence that
Finland must adjust immediately on joining the union next January to the CAP
price regime - and open its previously restricted market to agricultural
imports from the rest of the community.
With the EU already under strong international pressure to cut its existing
price supports, Finland can hardly expect to escape reforms of an
agricultural system even more heavily subsidised than the Union's.
But as Finland has maintained producer prices at levels up to 60 per cent
higher than those prevailing in the EU, this implies a big shock for Finnish
farmers. The government in Helsinki has negotiated the right to soften the
impact through a five-year programme of transitional aid worth FM4bn (Pounds
500m) next year.
But farmers complain it is still not clear how this will be implemented and
they say that, in any case, they will face reductions in income of between
10-45 per cent next year, depending on where their farms are located. Mr
Rantala says the average price he receives now for the 113,000 litres of
milk he produces per year - his chief source of revenue - is FM2.70 per
litre.
The EU price, he says, is around FM1.90 per litre. He does not yet know for
sure what price he will get if Finland joins the union.
'We had the minister of agriculture up here last week and he promised
decisions. But it's still not clear. None of the figures seem final. I don't
know what the price will be on January 1, but I have to vote on Sunday.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>FIZ  Finland, West Europe.
    QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
