<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / Balladur boards scandals bandwagon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The arrest of Mr Alain Carignon, mayor of Grenoble and a former minister, on
a new charge of corruption has set Prime Minister Edouard Balladur and his
political rivals vying with each other to be seen cleansing the country's
political system.
Mr Balladur, who said yesterday France's politico-financial scandals were
poisoning its political life, is hoping to avoid new legislation on
political funding by getting parties to agree on codes of conduct to
reinforce existing laws.
His four-point plan includes:
Audits of politicians' personal assets.
Making bids and awards on public contracts more transparent.
A reduction in election spending.
An ethics code for senior civil servants joining the private sector.
However, Mr Philippe Seguin, the National Assembly president, has convened
similar all-party negotiations in the parliament, with the aim of producing
legislative proposals by the end of November.
Mr Seguin does not share Mr Balladur's view that most of the current
scandals stem from the 1980s and can be dealt with by existing legislation,
notably the 1990 law on corporate contributions to political parties. The
fact that Mr Seguin also *something in here (HP) *
chairs a campaign committee for Mr Balladur's presidential rival, Mr Jacques
Chirac, does not incline him to minimise the damage to the government.
The detention of Mr Carignon marks a new threshold in the crackdown on
corruption. It is the first time a big-city mayor and ex-minister has been
locked up, even if briefly. Many Grenoble residents expressed shock at their
mayor ending up in a Lyons jail.
The Socialist opposition weighed in yesterday, claiming that with five of
ministers or former ministers under investigation the Balladur government
was 'in the process of coming apart'. But the edge of the attack by the
Socialists, themselves scarred from numerous scandals while in office, was
that the Balladur government had recently eased anti-corruption rules
requiring local councils to publish property deals and contract tenders, and
that the prime minister was indulging in a hypocritical 'media show'.
Mr Balladur is expected soon to have to replace his trade and industry
minister, Mr Gerard Longuet, who is expected to come under formal
investigation for financial and real estate improprieties. In July, Mr
Carignon left the government after being charged with 'receipt of fraud'.
The allegations linked Lyonnaise des Eaux's bail-out of a pro-Carignon
newspaper and the company's contract to run Grenoble's water supply.
The latest charge against Mr Carignon is that of 'passive corruption' -
receiving FFr13m (Pounds 1.55m) in corporate gifts, a free Paris apartment
and air tickets.
</TEXT>
