<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / Currency collapse fuels fear of higher inflation in Ukraine
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MATTHEW KAMINSKI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KIEV
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Ukraine's volatile currency, the karbovanets, has fallen sharply in recent
days, losing 6 per cent of its value against dollar yesterday and 12 per
cent since Monday, raising fears of higher inflation this winter.
The karbovanets, also called the coupon, sold at 100,000 to the dollar on
the open market yesterday, a 50 per cent fall since September 12.
The currency's latest fall follows Ukraine's decision last Friday to abolish
the government's artificial exchange rate and reopen free currency auctions.
The move was the first step in a comprehensive economic reform programme
announced by President Leonid Kuchma earlier this week, but, thanks to
inflationary credits inherited from the previous administration, the initial
impact of reform has been further destabilisation.
Unlike the panic caused by the Russian rouble's sharp fluctuations,
Ukrainians this week remained nonplussed about the latest devaluations.
Public confidence in the karbovanets has never recovered from last year's
hyper-inflation - when the annual inflation rate exceeded 10,000 per cent -
and, although many purchases are made in karbovantsi, few Ukrainians hold
their savings in the national currency.
This autumn's devaluation stems largely from a massive credit release to
agriculture this summer. The credits, authorised by parliament, derailed the
Ukrainian central bank's tight monetary policy, which brought the inflation
rate down to single digits during the first half of the year.
As a result, commercial banks are releasing around Kbv5,000bn (Dollars
53.2m) onto the currency exchange market each week, according Mr Mykola
Melnychuk, a Ukrainian national bank official.
Economists expect inflation, up from 2.9 per cent for the month of August to
7.3 per cent for last month, to rise to 60 per cent for this month.
The rise in inflation does not necessarily threaten the reform effort
because the International Monetary Fund, set to approve a Dollars 360m loan
by October 31, anticipated the karbovanets' decline and a resulting price
hike.
However, the Russian rouble's dramatic turns this week do pose a threat to
Ukraine and other former Soviet neighbours.
Ukraine and Belarus, among others, would be hit hard if Russian exporters
compensated for the rouble's fall by raising prices. Many former Soviet
republics depend heavily on imports from Russia.
Mr Stanislav Bukovinsky, Ukraine's deputy finance minister, told Interfax
news agency yesterday that Russian price increases for oil, coal and nuclear
fuel might, like last year, push the country into hyperinflation. Half the
country's imports are for Russian energy supplies, although gas - the
largest purchase - is fixed at a low dollar rate.
Ironically, before the collapse of the rouble zone in 1992 Moscow's
reformers warned that other former Soviet republics where exporting
inflation to Russia and thereby jeopardising Russian economic reform.
Mr Bukovinsky said the rouble's impact on Ukraine simply underscores the
need for quick economic restructuring to lessen dependence on Russian energy
supplies.
</TEXT>
