<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / SPD poised to tighten grip on upper house
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
No matter what happens in Sunday's election there will have to be a 'grand
coalition' between parliament's upper and lower houses. Even if the
governing coalition remains in power it will have to reach a new compromise
with the Bundesrat, the upper house which represents the 16 states and is
dominated by the opposition Social Democrats and Greens.
Moreover, the influence of the SPD is likely to increase after the Lander
elections in the eastern states of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and Thuringia
which also take place on Sunday. In western Germany, the SPD is expected to
comfortably win Saarland, headed by Mr Oskar Lafontaine, the party's
economics spokesman.
Both east German states are currently governed by the CDU in coalition with
the FDP. Opinion polls indicate that the FDP will fail to win 5 per cent of
the vote, the minimum required to enter the state parliaments, while the CDU
will not gain enough support to form a government on its own. In which case,
the CDU might be forced to form a grand coalition with the SPD.
In Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, opinion polls give the SPD 31 per cent of the
vote, compared to the 27 per cent it won in 1990, while the CDU's vote
remains stable at 38 per cent. The Party of Democratic Socialism, successor
to the former east German communist party, could gain at least 17 per cent
of the vote; the Greens could retain their 6 per cent share.
There is some temptation among SPD officials in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern to
form a government with the PDS, but this would not be tolerated by the
federal party organisation. 'Unless the Greens do very well, we could form a
grand coalition with the CDU,' an SPD official said.
The same possibility exists in Thuringia, where opinion polls show CDU's
share of the vote slipping from 45 per cent in 1990 to 41 per cent, while
the SPD's share has risen from 22 per cent to over 31 per cent. The Greens
might retain their 5 per cent. The PDS's share is expected to increase from
9 per cent to about 13 per cent.
A grand coalition in these two states would mean them sending CDU and SPD
representatives, instead of CDU and FDP ones. This would weaken the FDP's
influence in the Bundesrat while strengthening the SPD's. The 68 members of
the Bundesrat are not directly elected but chosen by the state governments.
Ten of the states are SPD-led, three are governed by the CDU, two have
CDU/SPD grand coalitions, while Bavaria is run by the Christian Social
Union, the CDU's sister party.
A stronger SDP hold on the Bundesrat could make life difficult for a CDU-led
coalition if it is returned to power.
In the last legislative period, 81 of the 504 laws approved by the Bundestag
were initially rejected by the Bundesrat. These were then passed to a
mediation committee consisting of members of both houses. Three laws were
rejected completely by the Bundesrat even after mediation.
Except for amendments to the constitution, which require a two-thirds
majority, a simple majority is required in the Bundesrat to block or accept
legislation approved by the Bundestag.
'Before we even debate draft laws in the Bundestag, it is crucial to sense
the mood in the Bundesrat,' a CDU deputy said, who spent three years trying
to reach a compromise on a compensation law for east property owners.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>DEZ  Germany, EC.
