<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / World markets rise as fears of increase in US rates diminish
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, GEORGE GRAHAM and FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
World bond and equity markets forged ahead yesterday as subdued US inflation
figures raised hopes that the Federal Reserve would delay its next move to
increase short-term interest rates.
US producer prices for finished goods fell by 0.5 per cent in September,
thanks to a drop in energy prices. The core index, which excludes food and
energy, rose by just 0.1 per cent, less than the markets had expected.
Producer prices are regarded by private sector economists as an early
indicator of price pressures. But economists at the Federal Reserve, the
central bank, regard the measure, along with the consumer price index, which
is published today, as backward-looking. Still, the positive news on
producer price inflation encouraged a surge in buying of longer-dated US
Treasury bonds. By late in the day the price of the benchmark 30-year
government issue was more than half a point higher, with the yield slipping
to 7.847 per cent.
Early on, this week's rally in US share prices, which had stalled on
Wednesday, appeared to gain a new lease of life. Within minutes of the
opening of the New York Stock Exchange, the Dow Jones Industrial Average
surged by more than 50 points, triggering the market's restrictions on
program-guided buying for the second time this week.
By the close, however, the Dow was up just 14.80 at 3,889.95 as the
confidence of investors buckled in the final hour, ahead of economic data
due out today.
European markets were pulled up by Wall Street's early strength. In London,
the FT-SE 100 Index closed up 41.4 points at 3141.9, while UK government
bonds gained half a point. In Germany, the DAX index rose 1.7 per cent in
after-market trading and government bunds were up by around seven-eighths of
a point.
In previous weeks, world markets reacted negatively to US statistics
indicating strong economic growth, which led traders to fear that the Fed
would move quickly to raise rates to quell inflationary pressures. But last
Friday's weaker-than-expected US employment data have led to a change in
sentiment.
