<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 94 / Clarke refuses to guarantee tax cuts before poll: Chancellor
dismisses suggestions of swing to right as 'laughable'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, yesterday refused to guarantee tax cuts
before the next general election.
He dismissed as 'laughable' suggestions that the Tory party should swing to
the right to counter Mr Tony Blair's more moderate Labour party.
Speaking after a cautious but well-received address to the Bournemouth party
conference, Mr Clarke indicated he would strongly resist efforts by
right-wing cabinet colleagues to dictate the government's policy towards
Europe.
With other cabinet ministers on the centre-left angry at attempts by
right-wingers to set the agenda, he said that Mr Michael Portillo, the
employment secretary, had been 'mistaken' in questioning the government's
commitment to Europe.
The chancellor said he had not changed any of his pro-European views and
remained in favour of the long-term goal of full economic and monetary union
 -an idea that is anathema to right-wing colleagues.
During a subdued debate on the economy in which he pledged that sustained
recovery would bring a strong upturn in the government's political fortunes,
Mr Clarke defused recent pressure from rightwing Tory MPs for tax cuts in
November.
He stressed that he was committed to a lower tax burden once public
borrowing had been brought under control. But he added later: 'Of course I
would be a happier man if it was this side of the election that I could make
the tax cuts. But I have no date circled in my calendar.'
Mr Clarke acknowledged that the strength of the economic recovery and the
sharp fall in inflation should allow him to cut several billions of pounds
in next month's Budget from his spending and borrowing targets. But he
insisted that the squeeze on spending would not be at the expense of
manifesto pledges to maintain the effectiveness of the welfare state. 'There
are areas of public spending where we are committed to growth.'
The chancellor added that the party should stick to the political ground on
which it now stood. 'The idea that the party starts marching off to the
right wing because Tony Blair is muscling in on it is slightly laughable.'
His comments came as cabinet ministers close to Mr John Major privately
voiced anger at the anti-European stance adopted by Mr Portillo and other
rightwing ministers such as Mr Peter Lilley and Mr John Redwood.
The ministers predicted Mr Major would use his closing speech to the
conference today to indicate that he would not allow the cabinet ministers
he once described as 'bastards' to dictate his strategy.
Brittan and Howe hit back on EU, Page 8
Joe Rogaly, Page 16
Observer, Page 17
</TEXT>
